<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Presents Budget Proposal to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Faced with an upbeat economic
outlook of six percent growth, the Nepali government announced
Tuesday an ambitious budget proposal for the fiscal year (FY)
starting on the coming July 16.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mahesh Acharya proposed at the parliament a
spending of about 92 billion rupees (1.3 billion U.S. dollars) for
the 2000/2001 FY starting on July 16, comparing to 77.24 billion
rupees (1.1 billion U.S. dollars) for the current FY (ending on
July 15 this year).
</P>
<P>
"The present budget represents an increase of 35 percent over
the current FY," said Acharya.
</P>
<P>
The increased expenses will go to hike in civil servants pay
and security arrangement among others.
</P>
<P>
The budget set aside 43.5 billion rupees (603 million U.S.
dollars) for regular expenditure, including expenses by the
government, military, police and judiciary, while 48.1 billion
rupees (688 million U.S. dollars) will be allocated for
development projects, including those relating to poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Acharya aims to raise 64.82 billion rupees (927 million U.S.
dollars) from revenue and new tax proposals, besides receiving
about 20 billion rupees (300 U.S. dollars) from bilateral and
multilateral grants.
</P>
<P>
To increase the revenue, Acharya proposed to widen the net for
income tax and to further hike VAT (value added tax), which was
implemented from last August.
</P>
<P>
Acharya's proposition to substantially increase the salary of
government employees, police, army and teachers is feared to
enhance inflation, further marginalizing the ordinary people,
about 50 percent of whom are living on an average daily income of
less than one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"The new budget should lay emphasis on poverty alleviation and
on agricultural production, on which 80 percent of people are
living," said Bharat Adhikari, a MP from the opposition CPN-UML (
Communist Party of Nepal-United Marxist and Leninist). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
