<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, May 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Sri Lankan military said Tuesday that it has
killed 116 Tamil Tiger rebels in its latest offensive operations
against the rebels in northern Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
A military spokesman said the army has recovered 14 bodies of
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said the government troops since Monday had launched a "
search and destroy" mission with newly acquired weapons at
Ariyalai, Sarasalai and Chavakachcheri in Jaffna which were
partially taken control by the rebels during the past three weeks.
(Sri Lanka-Troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The French telecommunications company France Telecom
has bought Britain's third largest mobile telephone company Orange
with 43.2 billion euros (38.88 billion U.S. dollars), France
Telecom announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
France Telecom bought Orange shares for 6.74 euros (6.07
dollars) each through payment in cash, share or repayment of debt
owed by Orange to the British telecommunications group Vodafone,
the former owner of Orange.
</P>
<P>
A new mobile phone company, New Orange, will be set up by
France Telecom, combining all its domestic and international
mobile phone services. (France-Britain-Telecoms)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's three main opposition parties Tuesday
submitted a non-binding censure motion against Prime Minister
Yoshiro Mori to the upper chamber over his remark that Japan is a
divine country with the emperor at its center.
</P>
<P>
The parties said in their bill to the House of Councilors that
Mori's remark ran counter to Japan's constitution, which
stipulates that sovereignty resides with the people. They added
that Mori lacks the qualifications necessary to be a prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The three parties are the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the
Japanese Communist Party (JCP) and the Social Democratic Party (
SDP). (Japan-Opposition-Mori)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's advance team for the historic inter-
Korean summit in Pyongyang on June 12-14 will leave for the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Wednesday through the
truce village of Panmunjom, the Unification Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 30-member team, led by Son In-kyo, a director-general of
the Unification Ministry, will stay in Pyongyang until June 12 to
conclude preparations for the summit between President Kim Dae-
jung and DPRK leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
The team, which consists of experts in communications, the
press, security and protocol, will inspect the president's
quarters and the summit venue, and consult with DPRK officials on
security and protocol issues. (SKorea-DPRK-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- U.N. Middle East envoy Terje Roed Larsen visited
south Lebanon Tuesday afternoon to verify whether Israel has fully
withdrawn from the area, a key condition set by Lebanon before
deploying its troops in the volatile region, Oriental radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. diplomat said that Larsen, who had been scheduled to
leave for Damascus later Tuesday, decided to spend the day in
south Lebanon and would instead travel to Syria Wednesday morning
for talks with Foreign Minister Faruk Sharah. (Lebanon-UN Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Leaders from both sides of Northern Ireland's
political divide Tuesday called on all parties to set differences
aside and get on with the job of governing.
</P>
<P>
As devolution was reinstated at midnight on Monday, Northern
Ireland's First Minister David Trimble and Deputy First Minister
Seamus Mallon resumed their posts at the head of the power-sharing
executive.
</P>
<P>
Eight of the Ulster Unionist, nationalist Social Democratic and
Labor Party (SDLP), and Sinn Fein ministers returned to their
offices. (Ulster-Politics)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Radio Fiji Tuesday night reported that Commodore
Bainimarama had chosen former army commander Ratu Epeli Nailatikau
as prime minister in his interim military government.
</P>
<P>
Ratu Epeli Nailatikau is the son-in-law of President Ratu Sir
Kamisese Mara, who has stepped down, and his wife, Tourism
Minister Adi Koila Nailatikau is one of 30 government hostages
being held by the armed group headed by Speight.
</P>
<P>
The military rulers announced Monday that Ratu Mara resigned
from his presidency. Recalling the president was one of conditions
put by Speight. (Australia-Fiji-PM) 
</P>
