<HEADLINE> Zambian President Candidate under Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Ben Mwila, a candidate running for
the Zambian presidential elections next year, was under
investigations over embezzlement of public funds.
</P>
<P>
A government minister said here Tuesday that Zambian
auditor-general is scrutinizing how public funds at the ministry
of defense were utilized when Ben Mwila was Defense Minister from
1991 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister and government spokesman Newstead Zimba
told a news briefing that a report which is being compiled by the
auditor general' s office would be handed over to President
Frederick Chiluba and it will be tabled at the national assembly.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, current Environment Minister, announced last Friday that
he would run for the presidency of the ruling Movement for
Multi-Party Democracy (MMD ) so as to pave the way for the general
elections next year.
</P>
<P>
A number of party cadres and the Nation Executive Committee of
the MMD called for Mwila's expulsion from the party after he
publicly announced his candidature.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest with a business empire
spanning manufacturing, construction, finance and fertilizers,
helped incumbent President Frederick Chiluba defeat former
President Kenneth Kaunda in the 1991 elections and now is seen as
a leading candidate to replace Chiluba in the next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
But Chiluba has indicated that he would ensure that Mwila does
not become the president and MMD has said it is not the time to
start the election campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
