<HEADLINE> U.N. Mine Experts Arrive in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A group of United Nations mine
experts arrived here Wednesday to study clearing mines in south
Lebanon, local radios quoted the spokesman of United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said Israel has given U.N. the maps of some
130,000 mines it laid in the occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He added that UNIFIL needs a special team to implement the
mine-clearing mission in south Lebanon. The peacekeeping force has
cleaned about 30,000 mines in the past 15 years in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Three children have been killed and 10 injured in mine
explosions in south Lebanon since Israel whirlwindly withdrew and
thousands of Lebanese flocked into south Lebanon to celebrate
liberation last week.
</P>
<P>
Israel accelerated its troop pullout in face of the swift
collapse of its proxy militia, the South Lebanon Army, under
pressure from resistance guerrillas, and complete the task a week
ago, bringing its 22-year occupation to a hasty end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
