<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Offers Full Cooperation with U.N.: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Foreign Minister Faruk
Shareh said on Wednesday his country is ready to "cooperate fully"
with the United Nations to ensure the full implementation of U.N.
resolutions concerning Israeli troop withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Shareh made the pledge to the official Syria Arab News Agency
after meeting with U.N. special Middle East envoy Terje Roed-
Larsen, who arrived here Wednesday morning from south Lebanon for a
brief visit to Syria.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Shareh called on the United Nations to
shoulder its responsibilities in ensuring the implementation of
relevant U.N. resolutions, especially resolutions 242 and 338, in
order to establish fair and comprehensive peace, security and
stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Larsen briefed Shareh on the work of the U.N. mission in south
Lebanon and the progress made so far in implementing U.N. Security
Council Resolution 425 of 1978, which calls for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. will not issue any report on the withdrawal
until it verifies that Israel has completely pulled out its troops
from the occupied Lebanese territories, Larsen told reporters after
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy said he and Shareh had discussed the issue of
deploying the Lebanese army in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon refused to deploy government troops in south Lebanon
vacated by Israel until the U.N. has verified that the Israeli
withdrawal is complete.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said that during the talks Shareh informed him that Syria
has agreed that the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon should
not include the disputed Shebaa Farms, an area both Lebanon and
Syria claimed as Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Larsen was due in Beirut later Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
