<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens Peru on Funds for the Drugs War: Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States cannot exert
economic pressure on Peru by cutting the assistance it gives to
the South American country to fight drug trafficking, said Fight
Against Drugs Consuming Commission (CONTRADROGAS) president
Alejandro Aguinaga on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign assistance is important, but they cannot limit us
using that issue," said the official in relation to the
possibility that the United States might reduce its economic
support to combat drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Aguinaga dismissed the possibility that the U.S. government
might apply some kind of sanctions to Peru because of the
allegedly irregular electoral process of Sunday, by which
President Alberto Fujimori was elected for a third mandate.
</P>
<P>
The United States threatened Peru with economic and political
sanctions and the cut of military assistance if it did not carry
out transparent elections, through Resolution No. 43, promoted by
U.S. Congress and backed by President Bill Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
According to Aguinaga, the relation between foreign aid and
what Peru invests in the war on drugs is one-to-seven, and if that
support is reduced the country would have to make an effort to
achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
"The Peruvian government investment in the war on drugs
surpasses 700 million dollars, much more than all the external
assistance the country receives for that purpose," said the Fight
Against Drugs Consuming Commission president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
