<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price War Hits Sainsbury's Profits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sainsbury's, the UK's second biggest
supermarket group, has announced a steep drop in profits - blaming,
in part, the ongoing food price war.
</P>
<P>
Underlying pre-tax profits for the year to April 3 crashed 23
percent from 755 million pounds to 580 million pounds, although
sales rose 6.3 percent to 17.4 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
Sainsbury's said Wednesday the profit plunge was due to a poor
performance by its core supermarket business caused by vicious
price-cutting measures and higher staff and property costs.
</P>
<P>
The supermarket said it would be concentrating its program on
improving outlets in the battle to regain custom lost to other
food retailers such as Tesco and Wal-Mart's Asda chain.
</P>
<P>
Peter Davis, the group's newly installed chief executive, said:
"These results demonstrate that while we have two very strong
business .... we need to focus our efforts on our core supermarket
business."
</P>
<P>
But he admitted that recovery of the supermarket operations
would take time and he was going to concentrate on improving
Sainsbury's stores.
</P>
<P>
Peter also announced that at least 5000 jobs would be created
over the 12 months across the business. Over the last year the
group opened 20 new stores. This year it plans to open a further
13 and extend 35 others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
