<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Bank Official Urges Reforms and Cutting Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Italy Governor Antonio Fazio
warned Wednesday that Italian business and industry are losing
ground in Europe on the competition and technological innovation
fronts and argued that a reduction in fiscal pressure and reforms
are urgently needed to free the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience which included the Italy's leading
authorities, bankers, economists and business and industry figures
gathered for the Bank of Italy's annual assembly, Fazio declared
that the time has come to unchain the nation through reforms to
revive investments, productivity and job creation.
</P>
<P>
"The positive phase of the international trend provides the
occasion to undertake reforms of the rules, public spending,
taxation," he said in his final considerations report delivered on
the red-letter day on the calendar for the Italian economy and
finance.
</P>
<P>
Citing statistics, economic indicators and forecasts and his
hopes for a degree of political stability, the central banker
signaled his desire to see a radical change of the public
administration, more equitable budgetary policy and greater
clarity in the roles of management, the government and labor.
</P>
<P>
On another front, Fazio said, "the New Economy is nothing other
than reorganization of the production set-up applied through
information and innovation. Small and medium-size enterprises in
the south can draw benefit from these great advances," he affirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
