<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Declares War with Eritrea Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhao Yi
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles
Zenawi announced Wednesday that Ethiopia's war against Eritrea was
over after Ethiopia has "liberated" all its territories lost to
Eritrea in their two- year border conflict.
</P>
<P>
Briefing resident diplomats and representatives of
international agencies here, Meles said "as of today we (Ethiopia)
have verified that all our territory is cleared from the invading
army of Eritrea".
</P>
<P>
Meles made the remarks after the Ethio-Eritrean indirect talks
held in Algiers agreed on a peaceful arrangement for the secession
of hostilities between the two Horn of African countries.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea began a new round of heavy fighting along
their disputed borders on May 12, with Ethiopian troops claiming
to get an upper hand in the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's objective "to reverse the aggression by peaceful
means, if possible, and by force, if necessary, has been
fulfilled", Meles said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the government of Ethiopia has
changed the instructions for its army from attacking the enemy to
clear the territory to securing and protecting the liberated
areas.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia demanded the international community to provide
security guarantee to implement withdrawing its troops to the
positions before May 6, 1998, when the two countries started their
border conflict.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "the high grounds in Shelao area of the Badme
front as well as those between Zalambessa and Senafe" must remain
clear of the Eritrean troops.
</P>
<P>
Badme, Zalambessa and Senafe are three towns situated in the
western and central border between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
"We will remain where we are on the Zalambessa front," he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister added that his country will continue to
redeploy its forces in the western front and the troops will clear
and secure the newly liberated areas in the eastern front.
</P>
<P>
Meles noted that as soon as agreement for secession of
hostilities is reached, Ethiopia is ready to go back to the border
boundaries before May 6, 1998, provided Ethiopia has the security
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
"We feel we have struck to our word and our promise that the
war will end as soon as all our territories are liberated -- not a
minute earlier, not a minute later.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus now is on the diplomatic negotiations front...If the
Eritrean army insists on extending 'warm welcome' to our army then
we will have no quarrels about making good of it, " Meles said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
