<HEADLINE> Palestinian Prisoners Suspend Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails,
who have been on a hunger strike since earlier this month, have
decided to suspend their hunger strike as of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A commission for solidarity with Palestinian prisoners has also
told its members to suspend a sit-in in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Palestinian and Israeli negotiators met
Tuesday in the West Bank town of Jericho to discuss the release of
more Palestinian prisoners and the conditions of hunger-striking
Palestinian prisoners in various Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks made no apparent progress on Palestinian
demands for the release of more than 200 Palestinian prisoners held
by Israel. Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat said Israel
promised an answer within a week.
</P>
<P>
Informed Palestinian sources said Israel initially agreed to
release an undisclosed number of Palestinian prisoners. The
Palestinian side has been demanding the release of 1,650
Palestinian prisoners from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Israel claimed it has released 383 Palestinian political
prisoners since the signing of the Sharm el-Sheikh memorandum last
September.  Hundreds of Palestinian prisoners started a hunger
strike earlier this month, demanding their release and in protest
against the inhumane treatment they received in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
A demonstration in support of the prisoners on May 21 turned
into bloody clashes between the Israeli troops and the
demonstrators, which killed 6 Palestinians and wounded over 1,000
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
