<HEADLINE> Cyprus Calls for Substantial Negotiations in Third Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government will take part
in a fourth round of proximity talks on Cyprus only if the third
round of talks warrants for a continuation, government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Papapetrou said President
Glafcos Clerides will go to the third round of talks, "prepared for
substantial negotiations, to discuss everything with good will and
in a positive spirit."
</P>
<P>
"If the Turkish (Cypriot) side has the same stance then there
will be real prospects to continue," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island in reaction to a coup in Nicosia
engineered by the junta then ruling Greece.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the two
communities were held last December and February this year, during
which the two sides put forward their views on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
A third round of talks is scheduled to start on July 5 in
Geneva. The Cyprus government believes it must be upgraded and
negotiations should begin to pave the way for a settlement on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said the Cyprus government does not participate in a
procedure for the sake of participating.
</P>
<P>
He said President Clerides is not prepared to continue what was
done in the previous rounds of talks, especially when no concrete
prospects are created for this process to continue.
</P>
<P>
"The third round of talks must prove that there are real
prospects to move forward on the problem," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
