<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New-Home Sales Fall Sharply in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Sales of new homes in the United
States fell 5.8 percent in April to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 909,000 units, the largest fall in seven months, the
Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
April's decrease in new-homes sales, the biggest monthly
decline since a 7.2 percent decrease in September, suggests that
rising mortgage rates may finally be slowing the red-hot housing
market.
</P>
<P>
In other economic news, the government said that consumers
spent 5.26 billion U.S. dollars shopping in cyberspace during the
first quarter of this year out of total retail sales during the
period of 747.8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
That means of every 100 dollars in retail sales rung up during
the January-March quarter, 70 cents was spent online, the Commerce
Department estimated.
</P>
<P>
The first-quarter figures on e-commerce represented an increase
of 1.2 percent from fourth-quarter online sales of 5.20 billion
dollars. The Commerce began three months ago issued quarterly
estimates of e-commerce activity in an effort to show the impact
the Internet is having on the American economy.
</P>
<P>
The 5.8 percent drop in new-home sales came on the heels of a
revised 5.8 percent jump in March sales, which had pushed the pace
to 965,000 homes, the second-highest level in history. In November
1998 sales hit an all-time high rate of 995,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe there will be increasing signs in coming
months that higher interest rates are starting to slow the economy.
Since last June, the Federal Reserve has increased interest rates
six times in an effort to raise borrowing costs enough to slow
consumer demand for big-ticket items like homes and autos and keep
overall inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by the Fed's rate campaign, mortgage rates have been
rising, and 30-year mortgages now are at 8.62 percent, up more
than a full percentage point from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The decline in home sales was accompanied by a drop in the
median price of homes, which declined 2.2 percent to 161,400
dollars, the lowest level since last October. The median price,
the point at which half the homes sold for more and half for less,
had risen to 165,000 dollars in March.
</P>
<P>
The average home price continued to rise despite the drop in
April sales, climbing to 208,000 dollars, up 2.2 percent from 202,
300 dollars in March.
</P>
<P>
The national sales decline reflected weakness in all areas of
the country except the Northeast, where sales were actually up 8.6
percent to an annual rate of 88,000 homes in April.
</P>
<P>
Sales fell by 15.4 percent to an annual rate of 153,000 homes
in the Midwest. They were down 11.5 percent to an annual rate of
246,000 units in the West and were off a slight 0.7 percent to 422,
000 units in the South. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
