<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Index Dips in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The index of U.S. leading economic
indicators declined slightly in April, pointing to a continuation
of the economic expansion during 2000 but at a slower pace, the
Conference Board said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Board, a prominent research group, said in a report that
the leading index dropped 0.1 percent at 106.0 in April, following
a 0.1 percent increase in March and a 0.3 percent decline in
February. The index stood at 100 in 1996, its base year.
</P>
<P>
During the six-month span through April, the leading index rose
by 0.5 percent with six of the ten components advancing, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"The biggest risk to the ongoing expansion, which in June will
be in its record 111th month, remains the interest-rate increase
at hand and the prospect of still more action by the Federal
Reserve Board," said Conference Board Economist Ken Goldstein. "
The data suggest that some sectors many be begging to respond to
Federal tightening."
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates six times since last June
in an effort to cool off the U.S. economy and keep inflation at
bay.
</P>
<P>
The report said five of the ten indicators that make up the
leading index rose in April. The positive contributors to the
index were money supply, average weekly manufacturing hours,
vendor performance, stock prices and consumer expectation.
</P>
<P>
The largest negative contributors to the leading index in the
same month were manufacturers' new orders for consumer goods and
materials and the interest rate spread, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
