<HEADLINE> Peruvian Government Starts Diplomatic Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori's
government started Wednesday a diplomatic campaign to prevent
international banishment and convince the world of the legitimacy
of his reelection for a third presidential mandate.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Alberto Bustamante went to United States where
he spoke at an assembly called with urgency for Wednesday by the
Organization of American States Organization (OAS) Permanent
Council in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The assembly analyzed the report from Eduardo Stein, head of
the OAS observers mission, which withdrew from Peru, and said that
the electoral process of that country was vitiated with
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian ambassador to the regional organization in Washington
Beatriz Ramacciotti presented a report about the elections and
repeated the position of her government that the electoral process
was clean and transparent.
</P>
<P>
The United States representative requested the assembly during
the same meeting to discuss the Peruvian case during the OAS
general annual assembly, that will be held Sunday in Canada,
attended by the foreign ministers of the continent.
</P>
<P>
Peruvian Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies said that he
will go to Canada to answer to all the concerns of his colleagues
about the second electoral round of Sunday, May 28.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori was the only contestant for the runoff election after
the withdrawal of his  rival Alejandro Toledo, who had
conditioned his participation in the election to their
postponement for June.
</P>
<P>
De Trazegnies said that the foreign ministers of the neighbor
countries of Peru have stated their respect to the principle of no
intervention in the internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian Foreign Ministry has started contacts with the
governments of Ecuador, Cuba, Venezuela, and Mexico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
