<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Hails Israel's Admission to U.N. Regional Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday welcomed Israel's admission to a U.N. regional
group after being excluded for more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
The West European and Others Group(WEOG) last Friday admitted
Israel as its temporary member, paving the way for Israel's
eventual election to key U.N. bodies.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his spokesman's office, Annan said "I
was pleased to learn of the decision of the Western European and
Others Group to admit Israel as a temporary member."
</P>
<P>
"This step rectifies a long-standing anomaly. It should pave
the way for Israel to participate on an equal footing with other
nations in the main organs of the United Nations, and it upholds
the principle, enshrined in the Charter, of equality among all
Member States," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"This decision is particularly welcome at a time when all
people of goodwill are hoping for early and decisive progress in
the Middle East peace process," Annan added.
</P>
<P>
Israel is the only U.N. Member State which is barred from any
of the organization's five regional groups until WEOG admitted it
as its temporary member last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israel's admission to WEOG is for an initial four years, after
which it will be subject to confirmation by the group's other
members.
</P>
<P>
WEOG includes the 15 members of the European Union, Australia,
New Zealand, Canada, Turkey and a number of other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
