<HEADLINE> Schools Shake-up Proposals Include Large Pay Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Edinburgh, May 31 (Xinhua) - Plans for a major shake-up in
Scotland's schools were unveiled Wednesday, including a new class
of better-paid "super-teachers".
</P>
<P>
The proposals include big pay rises for all teachers and
changes in their contracts to create a more flexible profession.
</P>
<P>
The report by the independent McCrone committee, set up by
Scotland's coalition government to review teachers' pay and
conditions, is regarded here as the most far-reaching review of
teaching for a generation.
</P>
<P>
The McCrone report includes plans for a twin-track career
structure, which would mean the best classroom teachers earning
most.
</P>
<P>
The committee argues there should also be more money for
teachers who take on responsibilities outside the classroom.
</P>
<P>
However, it was given a cautious welcome by the leader of
Scotland's largest teaching union, the Educational Institute of
Scotland (EIS). Its general secretary Ronnie Smith said teachers
would decide in a ballot whether they were prepared to accept the
changes.
</P>
<P>
Scottish Education Minister Sam Galbraith said the EIS had
argued for a twin-track system for teachers. "We believe teachers
should be able to advance in their careers without necessarily
having to take on management responsibilities."
</P>
<P>
The report would require careful consideration before there
were any steps towards implementation, he said, adding he would be
carrying out a series of consultations over the summer with
employers, teachers and others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
