<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scotland's Companies Take Time Over Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EDINBURGH, May 31 (Xinhua) - Scotland's leading listed
companies taken an average 34 days to pay their bills, and their
suppliers are suffering as a consequence, according to the figures
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Small Business (FSB) revealed that the worst
late payer among plcs is Weir Group, the engineering and
construction company, which takes 61 days to settle up.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures, a fifth of all companies in the UK
take more than 60 days to pay. Among them 16 are named as taking
more than 200 days to settle up.
</P>
<P>
Eleven companies have exemplary records, taking one day to pay.
Companies in the financial services sector top the payment
efficiency poll, with 67 percent paying within the normally agreed
timescale of 30 days.
</P>
<P>
Jim Torrance, the FSB's Scottish conveyor, said: "The
publication of these tables for the first time last year put
pressure on companies, but I am disappointed only a third are
paying their bills within the normal agreed time."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Weir Group blamed its poor performance on its
complicated network of operations that cover more than 100 plants
in 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have reduced the 61 days quoted to 59 days and are aiming
to reduce it even further," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
