<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Blasts Pan Am Flight in Split Second </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The explosive device that brought
down Pan Am Flight 103 in 1988 took a millionth of a second to
blow a hole in the fuselage of the aircraft, investigator told the
court on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Investigator Christopher Peel testified that the bomb was
inside a luggage container on the left side of the front of the
New York-bound aircraft, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Peel's testimony supported the prosecution's case that a
powerful explosion from inside a suitcase blasted apart the Boeing
747 jumbo killing 259 people on board and 11 others on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Though the defense team raised question regarding the exact
placement of the bomb, Peel, an aircraft expert from the British
Defense Evaluation and Research Agency, said that the bomb was in
the lower part of a luggage container and very close to the wall
of the container.
</P>
<P>
The fuselage of the aircraft was blown open a hole of 50
centimeters by 50 centimeters, Peel told the three Scottish judges.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution accused Libyans Abdel Basset al-Megrahi and Al-
Amin Khalifa Fahima of conspiracy to murder, murder and breaching
the international aircraft safety law.
</P>
<P>
The Lockerbie trial, that went underway on May 3, is expected
to last up to a year and is being held in a Scottish court under
Scots Law at Camp Zeist in central Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah would be sentenced to prison for life and serve their jail
term in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
If found not guilty or the court could not prove the case
against them, the two accused Libyans would be set free. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
