<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Warns Land-Hungry People Against Illegal Farm Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Vice President Joseph
Msika Wednesday warned land-hungry people in the country not to
pay for stands now being illegally sold at occupied peri-urban
farms.
</P>
<P>
"The government is the only one that can give land, not the war
veterans or anyone else," Msika said, noting that "there will be a
planned shifting of people."
</P>
<P>
The vice president praised the war veterans for their
demonstration, adding: "But we are a sovereign state with a
government."
</P>
<P>
"It is not the war veterans who can give land to the people.
When land is given, there is planning involved," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 white farms have been occupied by war veterans and
land- hungry communal people since February, this year and there
has been widespread illegal land sales at occupied farms around
Harare, the country' s capital.
</P>
<P>
The government gazetted amendments to the Land Acquisition Act,
allowing it to acquire farms without compensation. This is
expected to speed up the land resettlement program and end the
farm occupations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
