<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Resettle Landless People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
identifying 841 farms which it plans to acquire soon for
resettlement, said Chairman of the National Land Acquisition
Committee Joseph Msika on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview at his office with the Zimbabwe News Agency,
Msika said the government would embark on what he described as "an
accelerated resettlement program" through which people qualifying
for resettlement would be settled simultaneously at the acquired
farms in all the provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to Msika, who is also Zimbabwean Vice President, the
legal framework gazetted last week has allowed the government to
acquire the 841 farms without any impediments.
</P>
<P>
Through the amendments of the Land Acquisition Act, the
government will only pay for improvements to the farms.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the resettlement program, Msika said, the
government would overlook infrastructural development and only
concentrate on essential services such as the provision of water
and graded roads, and the demarcation of the farms.
</P>
<P>
"We are now identifying the 841 farms province by province. Our
plan is to settle people simultaneously in all the provinces," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is identifying war veterans, landless
and communal people who qualify for the resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
The people to be resettled would include people with master
farmer certificates, an aptitude for farming and war veterans, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Like in the past, he said, 20 percent of each of the resettled
farms would be allocated to war veterans.
</P>
<P>
He could not say how many people would be resettled on the 841
farms as the government is still working out the exact figures.
</P>
<P>
"What we are considering is the land carrying capacity. We have
to take into account its sustainability," he said, stressing that
"we will not ruin the land."
</P>
<P>
On the war veterans' demands that the resettlement should start
before the June 24 and 25 parliamentary elections, the vice
president could not specify the exact date when people would be
moved into the acquired farms.
</P>
<P>
He said they are still working out the timetable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
