of calm and constructive dialogue with Zimbabwe, British High
Commissioner (ambassador) Peter Longworth said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Zimbabwe and the United Kingdom have been traders for a long
time," he said. "I hope it will not be long before we get back to
the situation where the bulk of our effort is directed at building
up volumes and quality of our two-way trade."
</P>
<P>
Longworth made the remark at the launch of "Trade Partners
U.K." aimed at encouraging more British firms to develop an
international dimension to their business by developing new
opportunities in overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain, which was Zimbabwe's second largest
trading partner, would continue to buy beef, tobacco, minerals and
horticultural products.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, he said, was buying a wide range of goods from UK
including heavy machinery and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
He said it was no secret that Zimbabwe's economy was going
through hard times and the UK and other trading partners had
noticed this in the disappointing performance of their exports.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Zimbabwe and Britain have soured over the
stance taken by Zimbabwe to compulsorily acquire white-owned land
for resettlement of landless blacks which has been described by
the British as the "land grab". 
</P>
