<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves $65 Million Credit for Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved a credit
of about 65 million U.S. dollars to help the Zambian government
provide basic services to the poor communities of the country, a
press release by the bank said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 10-year program will help the government empower the local
authorities to improve governance and efficiency in service
delivery and increase access to basic social services, according
to the press release issued by the World Bank country office based
in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Part of the money will be channeled to the community based
small projects such as basic social and economic infrastructure
including education, health, rural water supply and sanitation,
rehabilitation of community roads, natural resources management
projects and basic skills training.
</P>
<P>
Some of the money will be used in large infrastructure
benefiting more than one community such as health facilities and
market places.
</P>
<P>
The credit is on standard terms of 40 years maturity, including
10 years grace and the government and other donors will finance
the projects with an additional 9.5 million dollars, said the
press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
