<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Provides Lebanon Minefield Maps to UNIFIL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Israel Defense Forces (IDF)
have provided the peacekeeping United Nations Interim Forces in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) with maps of its minefields in the former
occupation zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The map transfer was ordered by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak shortly after Israel completed its redeployment along the
international border with Lebanon last week, a statement issued by
Barak's office said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This move will make the UNIFIL's tasks easier and safer to
remove mines in these fields, laid by Israel since it set up the
buffer zone in 1985 with a self-claimed aim to protect its north
from cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet approved the withdrawal in March and IDF carried
it out hastily in nearly 24 hours last week after South Lebanon
Army, the pro-Israeli militia, collapsed quickly under the pressure
of Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel is awaiting the United Nations' formal verification of
the withdrawal, a precondition it wanted to be met before it can
launch reprisal attacks against any future guerrilla attacks along
the border.
</P>
<P>
U.N. technical experts are continuing their work delineating the
boundary along the border line marked by the British and the French
colonial mandate in 1923, which has been generally accepted as the
international border between Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Only when the cartographers have finished their works can the U.
N declare Israel's withdrawal in compliance with U.N. Security
Council resolutions 425 and 426.
</P>
<P>
Resolutions 425, adopted in 1978 after Israel's first invasion,
demanded an immediate and unconditional withdrawal of Israeli
troops from Lebanon. But only until last year did Israel agreed to
comply with the resolution, as it was considering a pullout amid
mounting casualties in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli television reported Tuesday that U.N. special envoy
Terje Roed-Larsen and Danny Yatom, Barak's security adviser and
confidant, had agreed in a meeting on the placement of the entire
border. However, the report had not got confirmation from Barak's
office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
