<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister: Shas Not to Trade Votes with Pardon for Deri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Health Minister Shlomo
Benizri Wednesday refuted a report that the ultra-Orthodox Shas
Party will vote for the presidential candidate who will grant a
pardon to its former leader Aryeh Deri convicted for financial
fraud.
</P>
<P>
Benizri, also from Shas, said the pardon demand came from one of
Rabbi Yitzhak Kadourie's aids, not from the Shas party itself.
</P>
<P>
Deri, former leader of Shas, has been sentenced to four years in
prison for financial fraud and is now waiting for a supreme court
decision on his appeal.
</P>
<P>
Benizri said Shas is now considering which candidate to support,
but this has nothing to do with pardon for Deri. He said Shas's
spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef may tell its Knesset
(parliament) members to vote as they please.
</P>
<P>
Shas, the largest parliamentary grouping after Labor and the
opposition Likud, is believed to hold the key to who will win when
the secret ballot casting for a new Israeli president is held on
July 31. So far, Shas has refrained from officially announcing who
it will support.
</P>
<P>
The race for Israel's eighth president is now underway between
Regional Cooperation Minister Shimon Peres, candidate named by the
Labor-led One Israel, and Likud's candidate Moshe Kotsav.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that Peres, now a cabinet minister in power and an
internationally known figure, takes lead over Kotsav, Knesset
member and former tourism minister.
</P>
<P>
Despite the reassuring findings, Peres is still concerned about
Shas's vote in the secret ballot casting. Analysts here observe
that although he has a good relationship with Rabbi Yosef, Shas
will hard-pressed to vote against Katsav, who like Shas supporters,
is a Sephardic Jew with origins in the Arab world and more
observant of Jewish law than Peres is.
</P>
<P>
Katsav's camp is fully aware that if Shas does not officially
back the Likud candidate, Katsav has no chance of winning. Peres,
on the other hand, might win without Shas.
</P>
<P>
There have been speculations that Shas may take advantage of the
election to ask for prices. The demand of a pardon for Deri might
be one of them.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the speculation, Deri said on Tuesday that he does
not want a pardon from the would-be president, because he believed
the good decision would be in the court, not in the president.
</P>
<P>
Benizri said most of the Shas Knesset members will vote for one
candidate and will not divide their votes. He noted that while the
legislators can prefer to vote the one closer to Shas, it does not
necessarily mean they will vote Katsav, because Peres has been very
close to Shas and to Rabbi Yosef.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Cabinet Minister Haim Ramon, the manager for
Peres' campaign, said he expects Shas Leader Yosef only to make a
decision close to the July 31 election date. He hoped Yosef's
admiration for Peres will influence his decision to back Peres.
</P>
<P>
President Ezer Weizman, 76, Sunday announced his decision to
resign on July 10 following attorney general's report on his gift-
taking scandal, three years before the end of his term.
</P>
<P>
The 120-member Israeli parliament will elect a new president on
July 31. On the following day, the new president will be sworn in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
