<HEADLINE> Syria Accepts Israeli Lebanon Withdrawal: U.N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Syria has fully accepted Israel's
withdrawal from south Lebanon, without demanding Israel pull out
from the disputed Shebaa Farms, said U.N. special envoy to the
Middle East Terje Roed-Larsen here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said in a statement that Syria and the United Nations
agreed "on every matter" related to the pullout, which was hastily
completed last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Syria did not require the withdrawal include the Shebaa Farms,
the envoy told reporters after meeting with Syrian Foreign Minister
Faruk Shareh.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said that during the talks Shareh had informed him that
Syria accepts fully U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's report to
the U.N. Security Council on May 22 "which also defines the lines
for the purpose of confirming the withdrawal."
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the Security Council Annan recommended
the Shebaa Farms be dealt with as part of the area patrolled by a
U.N.force monitoring a 1974 Israel-Syrian ceasefire and not as
coming under the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), formed in
1978.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon refused to deploy government troops in south Lebanon
vacated by Israel until the U.N. has verified that the Israeli
withdrawal was complete.
</P>
<P>
Last week Shareh told a press conference in Lisbon, Portugal,
that an Israeli withdrawal should include the Shebaa Farms, an area
both Lebanon and Syria claimed as Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
However, Israel said the area is part of the Golan Heights it
captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war, whose fate should
be decided during the peace talks with Syria after they resume.
</P>
<P>
Larsen arrived here from south Lebanon Wednesday morning for a
brief visit to Syria, the major power broker in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
