<HEADLINE> Grand Funeral Held in Honor of Canada's Hockey Hero </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A grand funeral is being held
Wednesday morning in Montreal in honor of Canada's hockey hero
Maurice Richard, known as "Rocket" among hockey fans throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien and Quebec Premier Lucien
Bouchard are among hundreds of mourners at the funeral being
staged in the Notre-Dame Basilica.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of other people are gathering outside to say good-bye
to Richard, whose prodigious talents thrilled hockey fans for 18
years. He was seen to win his last Stanley Cup in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Remembering Richard has consumed Montreal and the rest of the
country since the 78-year-old national hero died Saturday in
hospital after a long battle with abdominal cancer and Parkinson's
disease.
</P>
<P>
In North America, players and 19,000 fans paid a brief tribute
to the Rocket's memory prior to Tuesday's start of the Stanley Cup
final series between the Dallas Stars and the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
