<HEADLINE> Turkey Urged to Change Policy Toward Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Undersecretary of Defense
Dimitris Apostolakis Wednesday urged neighboring Turkey to change
its policy toward Athens.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 2nd Greek-British defense industries conference
in Athens, Apostolakis said that the Turkish leadership must
understand that there was a need to draw up a different policy
toward Greece, and that would be firm and lasting in harmony with
international law and the existing treaties binding all sides.
</P>
<P>
He stated that Greece would continue to have a need for strong
and reliable deterrent force.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been
at odds over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea, and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The two long-time rivals have since last June begun to improve
their strained relations with the holding of several rounds of low-
level talks and the signing of a number of bilateral cooperation
pacts, but Greece has complained that Turkey has not done enough
in its efforts to better the bilateral relations between the two
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
