<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plane Carrying Eight People Crashes in South Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A plane carrying eight people is
believed to have crashed in Spencer Gulf in the South Australia
state on Wednesday, the Australian Maritime Safety Authority (AMSA)
said.
</P>
<P>
Both engines on the Piper Chieftain aircraft failed while it
was flying from Adelaide to Whyalla about 7 p.m. (local time).
</P>
<P>
The aircraft, operated by Whyalla Airlines, radioed both its
engines had failed approximately 15 nautical miles southeast of
Whyalla, AMSA said.
</P>
<P>
AMSA's national search and rescue organization AusSAR was
coordinating a search of the area, in coordination with South
Australian police.
</P>
<P>
Three fixed-wing aircraft were scouring the area and a number
of surface vessels were expected to join the search, AMSA said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
No further details were immediately available. 
</P>
</TEXT>
