<HEADLINE> Barak, Clinton to Meet in Lisbon Instead of Berlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
will hold talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Lisbon on
Thursday instead of Berlin as originally planned, Barak's office
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Barak will meet Clinton in Lisbon early Thursday morning after
which he will return home to attend a state ceremony marking
Jerusalem Unification Day, said the office in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will, during the summit meeting, discuss ways to
push the Middle East peace process forward in the wake of the
Israeli troop withdrawal from south Lebanon and study the
possibility of holding a three-way summit between them and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, said Barak's office on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived Tuesday in Lisbon, Portugal, for a three-day
visit, which is part of his current week-long European trip.
</P>
<P>
Barak had planned a visit to Washington two weeks ago, but
canceled it after violence in the Palestinian territories and heavy
fighting in south Lebanon flared up.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed its troop withdrawal from south Lebanon a week
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
