<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada Rejects to Declare Ceasefire in Mindanao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
rejected Wednesday to declare a unilateral ceasefire and allow 40
days of tranquillity in Mindanao, saying he will not allow Muslim
rebels take advantage of the situation.
</P>
<P>
According to Press Secretary and Presidential Spokesman Ricardo
Puno, the president made this clear to a multi-sectoral group that
met with him in the Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said the measures undertaken by the government to
uphold the constitution would result in a genuine peace for
Mindanao and would prevent the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) to regroup in the future.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, representatives of a multi-sectoral group
urged the president to unilaterally order a ceasefire and allow 40
days of tranquillity in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Puno said they sought a suspension of hostilities during this
40-day period, so they can bury the dead, carry the wounded,
harvest crops and salvage belongings.
</P>
<P>
The period, they added, would allow non-government
organizations to monitor the situation in the areas of conflict
and hold multi-faith dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Puno said the president told the group that the government will
be able to achieve its military objective in "a couple of days"
and this is to disable the rebel groups from regrouping and
harassing people.
</P>
<P>
Estrada also pointed out that the peace process with the MILF
has begun, with the first day of meeting successfully held on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"What the president would like to do is to assure the people
that the peace process will result in a genuine peace but he would
deny the rebels the capability of mounting armed attacks from the
satellite camps around Camp Abubakar," Puno said.
</P>
<P>
According to Armed Forces spokesman Rafael Romero, 24 camps of
the MILF had been overrun by the military since January this year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Puno said chief government negotiator
Robert Aventajado is confident he can secure the safe release of
21 persons held hostage in Sulu province after they were abducted
from Malaysia on April 23.
</P>
<P>
He said Aventajado expects talks to continue when he returns
Thursday to Sulu. "He is still optimistic some resolution can be
obtained and that discussions will continue," Puno said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Military Drops Plans for Civilian Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's military leaders Wednesday
dropped plans to set up a civilian interim government and said it
was possible the army may run the country better, the Australian
Associated Press (AAP) said.
</P>
<P>
Just hours after naming a civilian to take over as interim
prime minister, military leaders suddenly withdrew the nomination
of former diplomat Ratu Epeli Nailatikau, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
The head of the interim military government, army Chief Frank
Bainimarama, was quoted as saying the country was not yet ready
for a civilian administration to take over.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama Wednesday named Ratu Epeli as interim prime
minister and warned democracy may not return to Fiji for up to
three years.
</P>
<P>
But later in the day the military leader said he had deferred
the naming of an interim government until Fiji's political
situation had stabilized to the point where it could do its job of
rewriting the constitution and paving the way for new elections.
</P>
<P>
"The interim military government will be in place until it has
achieved its task in the release of all hostages at the parliament
complex and the return of all arms to the army," Bainimarama said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Military spokesman Filipo Tarakinikini confirmed Ratu Epeli
Nailatikau would not take up the prime ministerial post but, as a
former army commander, would sit on the military council, the AAP
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision to step back from a civilian interim
government was taken because the public service, judiciary and
police were all running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Even after the hostage crisis was settled, the military council
would consider whether to continue or hand over to a civilian
administration, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will have to review the whole situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We may run a much more efficient administration with the
military," Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
He said negotiations with Speight's supporters Wednesday "went
well" and would continue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Asked at a new conference on Wednesday when democracy would
return to Fiji, Bainimarama said: "As soon as we come up with a
new constitution."
</P>
<P>
"That could take three years," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also ruled out Chaudhry regaining the leadership.
</P>
<P>
"I am afraid Mahendra Chaudhry will no longer come back as
prime minister," Bainimarama said.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama assumed power and declared martial law in Fiji on
last Monday in an attempt to solve the crisis caused by the taking
hostage of former prime minister Mahendra Chaudhry and his
government on May 19.
</P>
<P>
The military is negotiating with supporters of armed coup
leader George Speight to win the release of Chaudhry and more than
30 MPs, being held at Suva's parliament house.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama has revoked Fiji's 1997, multi-racial constitution
and set up a military council to run the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
