<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Kicking off what aides describe as a week of positive, more
personal messages, Vice President Al Gore Tuesday accepted his
first endorsement from a national environmental group and all but
ignored George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
-- Boris Bezovsky, the influential tycoon who helped bring
Russian President Vladimir Putin to power, broke ranks with him
Tuesday, sharply criticizing Putin's attempt to rein in the
regional governors as an erosion of Russia's democracy.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Mariano Faget, 54, an acting deputy director of the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service with 34 years of service in
Miami, was convicted of disclosing official secrets, making
personal use of those secrets and lying to federal investigators
about his foreign business ties and meetings with a Cuban diplomat.
</P>
<P>
-- Hezbollah has started to operate in southern Lebanon much as
it does elsewhere, as a kind of parallel government offering
social services, development loans and reconstruction aid,
following the Israeli pullout.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Nasdaq composite soared a record 7.94 percent, or 254.37
points, to 3459.48, on widening hopes that the economy is headed
for a soft landing and that the Federal Reserve soon will stop
raising interest rates. Many investors, however, are skeptical the
rally will last, partly because volume remains weaker than normal.
The Dow Jones industrial also climbed, rising 227.89, or 2.21
percent, to 10527.13.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton arrived in Portual for the start
of a week-long European trip that will include talks with EU and
Russian leaders. The president is also to confer with Israel's
prime minister in Berlin Thursday.  
</P>
