<HEADLINE> Explosion-hit Indian Ship Rescued by Chinese Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- An Indian oil tanker, Pratibha
Yamuna, which caught fire because of explosion in East China Sea
last Saturday, has been dragged to an anchorage ground near
Shanghai by the Shanghai Salvage Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
All together 34 sailors of Pratibha Yamuna were picked up by
three Chinese fishing boats on May 27 and are currently staying in
a reception center in Wenling county, in east China's Zhejiang
province. Ships from SSB arrived at scene of the accident and put
out the fire within five hours.
</P>
<P>
On May 27, Pratibha Yamuna caught fire in the cabin. All the
crew abandoned ship within an hour after the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Gupta Rakesh, captain of the ship, said they had to abandoned
the ship because all the fire-fighting and lifesaving equipment
was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Rakesh said two crew members were slightly injured. The Indian
crew said they received medical treatment and accommodation, and
they have notified their relatives in India by telephone provided
by the local reception center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
