<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Asian Roundtable Focuses on Disclosure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD)'s Second Asian Roundtable on
Corporate Governance opened here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the Roundtable, attended by over 120 delegates
from many economies in Asia as well as international and regional
bodies such as the OECD, the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank, is disclosure, said Rafael Hui, Acting Financial Secretary
of Hong Kong, in an opening address.
</P>
<P>
"Disclosure is the most basic of corporate governance
principles because potential investors and shareholders must be
given sufficient information to make informed decisions about
their shareholdings and safeguard their interest in any given
company," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
"At the very least, one can say that better disclosure would
have allowed both governments and companies to react to underlying
economic problems in a more timely manner. Disclosure therefore is
a critically important element in the management of any modern
economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Roundtable meetings in the next two and a half days will
look at three important aspects of disclosure -- the role of the
board of directors in overseeing disclosure, accounting and audit
and non-financial disclosure such as related parties, ownership
structures and government policies, according to Hui.
</P>
<P>
Hui pointed out that while a number of factors were responsible
for causing the Asia economic downturn, it is now widely
recognized that the absence of or inadequacy in corporate
governance systems, particularly regarding corporate
accountability and transparency, had actually exacerbated the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He reminded people not to forget the need for corporate
governance reform today, when the recovery of many Asian economies
is steadily underway,
</P>
<P>
The First Asian Roundtable organized by the OECD was held in
Seoul in March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Loosens Restrictions on Overseas Investment in Mineral Exploration: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China has recently loosened its
restrictions on overseas investment in mineral exploration.
</P>
<P>
It is now possible for solely-funded foreign companies to
conduct mineral explorations in China and geological surveys, a
Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Previously, foreign investors must seek one or more Chinese
partners with survey qualifications and mining rights to set up a
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Weizhi, director of Geological Exploration Department
with the Ministry of Land and Resources, said that loosening
restrictions will allow more foreign investment in mineral
exploration in China.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate overseas investment in mineral exploration in
China, the ministry will also improve and streamline evaluation
and approving procedures.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry started a pilot program late last year by
delegating its power to a provincial government, authorizing the
land and resources administration in southwest China's Yunnan
Province to review, approve, register and issue licenses to
foreign companies that invest in exploration and mining activities
excluding petroleum, natural gas and radioactive minerals.
</P>
<P>
The official said the pilot program may extend to other areas
in western China, abundant in mineral resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
