<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Smoking Causes Heavy Costs in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco-related deaths, loss of
laborers and medical expenditure have led to heavy social and
economic costs to China, the world's biggest tobacco producer and
consumer, according to a national conference to mark Anti-Tobacco
Day in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Smoking was responsible for 514,000 deaths, while causing the
loss of 1.14 million laborers and bringing about 22.9 billion yuan
(2.7 billion U.S. dollars) in direct medical fees in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that 63 percent of male adults and 4 percent of
females smoke in China, and the number of teenager and female
smokers are growing.
</P>
<P>
Cigarettes now kill 2,000 people in China every day, and the
death toll is expected to climb to 8,000 per day, or three million
every year by the middle of the next century if current smoking
patterns persist.
</P>
<P>
Anti-smoking campaigners have long held that tobacco industry
brings more social and economic costs than economic benefits, and
China is no exception.
</P>
<P>
"The government should realize that potential and long-term
negative impact of the tobacco industry far outweighs the direct
economic benefits such as job opportunities and revenue," said a
researcher.
</P>
<P>
"We must curb smoking among China's youth through legislation,
administrative measures and education," Wang Ke'an, president of
the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
