<HEADLINE> Manila Satisfied With 1st Day Talks With MILF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Wednesday that the peace talks held on Tuesday between the
government and the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
were cordial, with the two sides establishing mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Eduarto Batenga, Philippine peace panel chairman, said in a
radio interview that the Tuesday meeting held in the southern
Cotabato City proceeded smoothly and "we're hopeful the talks will
result in something positive."
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday meeting was the first time that government and MILF
peace panel representatives met since the rebel group suspended
the formal negotiations in April.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's meeting, Batenga said the government formally
presented to the MILF a package of proposed political and economic
programs that would boost the peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to Batenga, the proposed government package centered
on attaining meaningful autonomy for Muslim Mindanao. He also
pointed out the need to conclude the talks by June 30, the
deadline set by President Josph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed a political package that the government feels
will meet the MILF's needs within the mandate of the constitution,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Batenga said the MILF asked for 15 days to study the political
package, and another 15 days to give its inputs through the
technical working committee, which would mean going beyond the
June 30 deadline.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed optimism that the decision of the national
government to issue safety and immunity passes to the participants
in the talks will enhance the cordial atmosphere of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The talks are scheduled to conclude on Wednesday, but the MILF
is asking for extension of the peace talks to have more time to
study the proposal of the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Armed Forces spokesman Rafael Romero said 75 MILF
rebels were killed in clashes with Army soldiers in Mindanao on
Monday and Tuesday despite the resumption of peace talks between
the government and the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said the MILF should stop all
violent actions in Mindanao and Metro Manila before any ceasefire
can be effective.
</P>
<P>
The 15,000-strong MILF has been fighting for an independent
Muslim state in Mindanao for more than two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
