<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SOS Village, Home for Orphans (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With a homely and loving atmosphere, the children have grown to
be confident and independent. They have also learnt to love other
people.
</P>
<P>
Tian Yongliang, an eight-year-old village boy, said that he
does not envy those boys and girls in ordinary families at all.
They are spoilt and often cry over trivial matters.
</P>
<P>
A chess coach, who once took a group of Chinese children abroad
for an international contest, said that some of the team members
from the children's village were the most considerate and best
behaved compared with children from ordinary families.
</P>
<P>
The children are also hard-working. Zhaoxian, a lute tutor,
said unlike those children from functional families, the three
children from the village in her class did not even miss one class
no matter how heavy it rained.
</P>
<P>
In China, all "mothers" are required to attend courses for
raising children before they enter the village, as most of these "
mothers" are still single, and have no experience on how to look
after children, said Wang Wuhai.
</P>
<P>
China now has nine SOS villages. The first village was
established in the port city of Tianjin in 1986. Funds come from
the Ministry of Civil Affairs and SOS Children's Villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
