<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SOS Village, Home for Orphans (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Guifang, a "mother" in the
SOS Children's Village in Kaifeng, central China's Henan Province,
was delighted to see her "oldest son", Liu Zhengguang, a 13-year-
old orphan, give a piece of candy to his youngest "brother", Niu
Shaohua.
</P>
<P>
Liu saw her parents being killed. He was hostile to everyone
when he arrived in the village. Three years of care and tender
love has changed Liu.
</P>
<P>
The SOS Children's Village is a social welfare institution
specially for the orphans. Most villages are composed of 15 to 20
families, with one mother and six to eight children living in an
independent house. The first one of the kind was set up in Austria
in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"Every orphan has a heartbreaking story to tell," said Wang
Wuhai, who runs the village. Most of them are premature and timid
and harbor prejudices. What they need is love and care. All the 14
mothers in the village believe the love and care will help them
grow into mature young adults.
</P>
<P>
Eight boys and girls in No.8 family were indifferent to their
mother Wang Liping when she arrived. Six months later, however,
they held a party for Wang's 23rd birthday, and they called her "
mum" for the first time. Moved to tears, Wang said, "That was the
best birthday present I ever got."
</P>
<P>
A variety of activities such as table-tennis contests, dancing
and singing troupes, and chess clubs are held in the village.
Village children can also learn drawing, calligraphy, computers,
and musical instruments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
