<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Real Estate Sector Attracts Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital in China's real
estate sector grew rapidly with the encouragement of the Chinese
government to promote the commercialization of the property market.
</P>
<P>
Actual foreign investment in the real estate sector was 700
million U.S. dollars in 1992, but rising to 6.22 billion U.S.
dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However the Southeast Asian financial crisis of 1997 depressed
the volume of utilized foreign capital to 5.27 billion U.S.
dollars in 1997 and 4.39 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
But, the experts noted, there are strong indications that the
upward trend has now resumed.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in real estate has been spreading form the
south to the north and from coastal areas to the hinterland, the
experts said.
</P>
<P>
The investment has transferred from coastal cities such as
Shenzhen, Xiamen, Guangzhou, Shanghai and Tianjin. In recent years,
it has expanded to some big inland cities including Chengdu,
Chongqing and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in real estate has also expanded from
commercial and service facilities and luxury residences to
ordinary residential buildings, and from new-district development
to old-district renovation.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, foreign investors have helped renovate such
commercial districts as Wangfujing, Xidan, Chongwen and Xuanwu
districts.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has signed 16 contracts worth two billion U.S. dollars
with foreign investors to renovate old districts.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, three Hong Kong consortia allied to renovate the
Zhabei District with an investment expected to surpass 10 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors are also helping renovate old urban districts
in Dalian, Guangzhou and Fuzhou.
</P>
<P>
More and more foreign-funded developers are involved. Of some
20,000 real estate developers nationwide, more than 5,000 are Sino-
foreign joint ventures or cooperative enterprises and over 1,000
are wholly foreign-owned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
