<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Giant Nasdaq Stocks Begin Trading On SEHK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Seven name-brand Nasdaq stocks --
Amgen, Applied Materials, Cisco, Dell, Intel, Microsoft and
Starbucks -- Wednesday began trading on the Stock Exchange of Hong
Kong (SEHK), the second largest exchange in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq Stock Market and Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing
Ltd. (HKEx) on Wednesday morning initiated a pilot program to
quote and trade the seven Nasdaq stocks, some of them being the
largest stocks with strong business interest in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Following the move, the Hong Kong stock market jumped 5.17
percent on Wednesday as a record gain in the Nasdaq index,
breaking its 250-day moving average at 14,700.
</P>
<P>
"This is a step forward in the development of global trading of
the world's leading stocks," Nasdaq Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer Frank G. Zarb commented.
</P>
<P>
"As our companies pursue business opportunities globally, it
makes sense that they offer their stock globally, reinforcing
their brand names in the minds of consumers and investors and
having the opportunity to access a lower cost capital."
</P>
<P>
However, the Nasdaq shares are being admitted for trading only,
but not "listed" on SEHK, and the Nasdaq retains responsibility
for the regulation of these companies to ensure that they meet the
relevant listing requirements, according to the Nasdaq chairman.
</P>
<P>
Charles Lee, chairman of HKEx, told the quoting ceremony here
Wednesday that this was the first pilot program to allow Nasdaq
stocks to be quoted for trading in an Asian time-zone exchange.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipate investors' interest will grow in parallel with
their investment knowledge in these stocks and with the extension
of their strategy to cover overseas stocks," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
The development of a liquid market in Hong Kong for global
stocks would help to establish it as an integral part of a 24-hour
global trading market linking the Asian, European and the United
States time zones, the HKEx chairman noted.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the pilot program followed the creation of
the joint website by the SEHK and Nasdaq in December 1998, which
provides share price information on Hong Kong and the U.S. listed
companies and was the first cooperative operation of its kind
between major securities markets.
</P>
<P>
HKEx Chief Executive Kwong Ki-chi also said at the quoting
ceremony that the pilot program offered investors in Hong Kong and
the region easier access to the stocks of some of the leading
companies which are shaping the development of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
The sustained economic development in Hong Kong, China's
mainland and the Asian region would create an enormous liquidity
pool in this time-zone which would attract the trading of quality
global stocks, and these would in turn provide opportunities for
investors to diversify their investments and an alternative
hedging market for cross-border trading activities, Kwong
explained.
</P>
<P>
The seven stocks will be quoted and traded in Hong Kong dollars
(one U.S. dollar is equal to 7.8 HK dollars). And trading of the
stocks will be subject to SEHK rules and Hong Kong Law including
the market manipulation provisions of the Securities Ordinance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
