<P>
According to ECantata.com officials, the company has already
provided 1.5 million U.S. dollars worth of on-line procurement
services to Chinese enterprises. For example, the China Three
Gorges Group and Nantong Machine Tools Co. Ltd. have managed to
cut procurement costs by 5-14 percent by buying goods and services
on the Internet. On-line procurement has also helped them shorten
the time of procurement by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zongping, chairman of the board of Nantong Machine Tools
Co. Ltd., said that on-line procurement will not only help Chinese
companies cut costs, but also create an equal footing for
suppliers by eliminating such practices as bribery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Govt Committed to E-commerce Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government was fully committed to
encouraging the development of e-commerce to maintain the region's
competitive edge and drive the overall economic growth, a senior
official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an e-commerce seminar for small and medium-sized
enterprises (SMEs), Hong Kong's Director of Information Technology
Services Lau Kam-hung said the government "has adopted various
measures to create an environment conducive to the adoption and
development of e-commerce in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"To ensure that electronic transactions can be performed
effectively over the Internet, we need a high quality and high
capacity telecommunications infrastructure to provide bandwidth
and services at affordable prices," he said.
</P>
<P>
To this end, Hong Kong has built broadband networks covering
all commercial buildings and available to over 80 percent of
households, Lau said, noting that to date the total capacity of
Hong Kong's submarine cables stands second only to that of Japan
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The government also encourages more competition and innovation
to further enhance Hong Kong's telecommunications systems for the
development of e-commerce, Lau said, referring to the provision of
a clear and supportive legal system by the Electronic Transactions
Ordinance which, he said, has enhanced the security in the conduct
of electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
The Ordinance, enacted in January 2000, also provides for a
voluntary certification authority recognition scheme under which
certification authorities (CAs) may apply to the government for
recognition on a voluntary basis in order to protect consumer
interests and to enhance users' confidence in electronic
transactions.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the use of public and private key pairs and
digital certificates also enables individuals and businesses to
establish the identity of the other party in electronic
transactions, ensuring the integrity and confidentiality of the
electronic messages transmitted over open communication network,
Lau said.
</P>
<P>
Citing other measures by the government to encourage e-commerce,
Lau said Hong Kong Post has become the first public certification
authority whose operation conforms to international security
standards to support various e-commerce applications in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To address the current problem of using Chinese in electronic
communications, the government published the Hong Kong
Supplementary Character Set in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
The government is taking the lead by introducing the Electronic
Service Delivery (ESD) scheme aiming not only to improve the
delivery of public services but also help to familiarize the
citizens with the e-commerce mode of delivery and give them the
confidence in electronic transactions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The open and common information infrastructure that we are
developing for ESD will serve as a platform for the private sector
to make use of in conducting e-commerce at a later stage," said
Lau.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from local SMEs and renowned organizations in
Australia, Japan, Singapore and the United States, attended
Wednesday's "Seminar on E-commerce in the New Millennium," an
event jointly organized by the Hong Kong Information Technology
Services Department (ITSD) and the Asia Oceanic Electronic
Messaging Association of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation to
enhance local SMEs' E-commerce awareness.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce is taking off in Hong Kong and other parts of the
world in the past one or two years. In 1999, the value of E-
commerce amounted to 96 billion U.S. dollars, and by 2003, the
figure is estimated to rise to between 1.4 billion and 3.2
trillion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
