<HEADLINE> Lebanese Parliament Holds First Meeting in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese parliament held a
historic special session Wednesday noon in Bint Jbeil town in south
Lebanon to commemorate the "martyrs" who died in Lebanon's 22-year
struggle against Israeli occupation, Oriental radio reported.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the Lebanese parliament met in south
Lebanon since 1978 when Israel invaded Lebanon and occupied part of
its southern territory.
</P>
<P>
The session, presided by Speaker and the leader of Muslim Shiite
Amal movement Nabih Berri, was held in a school of Bint Jbeil,
about 3 kilometer north of Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
Some 125 parliamentarians participated in the meeting and
several made speeches, paying tribute to those "martyrs" in
fighting with Israel.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,300 resistance guerrillas were killed in south
Lebanon in the 22-year Israeli occupation, which ended last week
with the withdrawal of all Israeli troops from south Lebanon where
Israel set up in 1985 a so-called security zone with the claim to
protect its north.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also mentioned the topic of reconstruction and
stabilization the life in the south. Oriental radio said a cabinet
member alluded that the government and parliament were thinking
over funding about 330 million U.S. dollars for reconstruction work
in south Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
