<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Indian Airlines (IA) will resume
its service to Nepal from Thursday after a five-month-long
suspension of its flights to Kathmandu following the hijacking of
its airliner to Kandahar, as Nepal has pledged beefed-up security
measures at Tirubhuyan airport, the local press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The IA early this month formally announced the resumption of
its daily flights from New Delhi and five flights a week from
Calcutta from June 1 after India and Nepal entered into a
memorandum of understanding during Nepalese Foreign Minister
Chakra Prasad Bastola's visit to New Delhi earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Under the document, the Nepalese authorities have accepted the
IA's demand for the installation of an additional X-ray machine as
well as a final check by Indian security personnel at Kathmandu
airport.
</P>
<P>
The flights were suspended on December 24 last year when the IC-
814 was hijacked by gunmen who commandeered the flight to Kandahar
in Afghanistan. 
