<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World No Tobacco Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The World No Tobacco Day was observed
Wednesday in Bangladesh in a befitting manner as elsewhere in the
world, with the slogan of this year "Tobacco kills: Don't be duped.
"
</P>
<P>
In observance of the day, different socio-cultural and anti-
smoking organizations have chalked out elaborate programs in the
city and other parts of the country, including seminar, rally,
discussion meeting, and distribution of leaflets.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health and Family Welfare has undertaken
various programs to mark the day. As a part of the program, the
ministry brought out a colorful rally Wednesday morning, which was
lead by State Minister for Health and Family Welfare M. Amanullah.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a discussion meeting was held in the afternoon, with
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad as the chief guest.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is responsible for 3.5 million deaths in the world
every year. Available data suggested nearly 47 percent men and 7
percent women are smokers. In Bangladesh, the situation is still
alarming. As many as 60 percent men and 30 to 40 percent women
smoke or use tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Besides, tobacco is hardly considered by smokeless women as
harmful. It is even a social custom to offer betel nut, smokeless
tobacco leaf or its products as a symbol of hospitality. As a
result, oropharyngeal and upper esophageal cancers are common in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the World No Tobacco Day, Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina said tobacco is a silent killer which kills the consumers
slowly and silently through smoking-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
Being informed that the national anti-tobacco organization and
Cancer Society have joined hands with the Ministry of Health in
its fight against tobacco, the prime minister wishes their efforts
all success and assures them of all possible cooperation from her
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Sells Dar Airport Handling Shares to Swiss Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has sold the
majority shares of the Dar es Salaam Airport Handling Company
Limited (DAHACO) at 4.8 million U.S. dollars to a Swiss firm to
conclude the privatization process of the formerly state-owned
handling company.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Parastatal Sector Reform Commission (PSRC)
said Tuesday here that Swissport International Limited, a
subsidiary of Swissair, acquired 51 percent shares while the
Tanzanian government controlled 49 percent, newspapers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
PSRC Chairman John Rubambe made the announcement after the
signing ceremony at which Swissport paid 480,000 U.S. dollars as a
conditional down payment for the purchase as stipulated in the
sale agreement to win exclusive rights to provide ground-handling
services at Tanzania's airports.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for the divestiture of DAHACO started in 1996 when
 Tanzanian government decided to reduce its shareholding in the
company by 16 percent to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Formed on April 27, 1984, DAHACO is the sole cargo
ground-handling company to airlines in Tanzania's two major
airports, the Dar es Salaam and Kilimanjaro International
Airports.
</P>
<P>
Signing the documents, Swissport President and Chief Executive
Officer Joseph In Albon said his company plans to apply modern
technology in the DAHACO operations as a strategy to make it more
efficient and competitive.
</P>
<P>
According to Albon, Swissport which was formed three years ago
is a specialized company in airport handling activities with
operation in over 100 countries worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
