<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Former President Claims Innocence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's former President Canaan
Banana, who was ordered to go to prison on Monday for a year for
sexual offences including sodomy, claimed that he was an innocent
man, the daily Herald reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The former president, after consulting his defense lawyer
Advocate Chris Andersen on Tuesday, told local reporters that his
conviction and sentence were "politically motivated".
</P>
<P>
However, Banana refused to say whether he is considering
applying for presidential pardon, his last option if he is to stay
out of prison.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruled on Monday that Banana should serve a
one-year jail term for 11 counts of sexual offences.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered the former president to pay 250,000
Zimbabwean dollars (6,500 U.S. dollars) as restitution to his
former aide-de-camp Jefta Dube, who is one of the sodomy victims.
</P>
<P>
If he fails to pay the amount, the court said, then another two
years in jail that has been suspended on condition that he pays
would become effective. 
