<HEADLINE> China Beats U.S. at Women Soccer Pacific Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- China downed the United States 1-0
in their Pacific Cup women's soccer clash at Bruce Stadium in
Canberra Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The goal came five minutes from the end when Chinese captain
Sun Wen placed the ball past U.S. goalkeeper Siri Mullinix.
</P>
<P>
The penalty came when Sun, the Asian player of the year, was
brought down by U.S. substitute Danielle Slaton.
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Ma Yuanan kept the victory in perspective.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. were without several of their top players," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we are not at our peak yet either," he said.
</P>
<P>
American team boss April Heinrichs said any loss was a big
disappointment for the world champion.
</P>
<P>
"But we learn from our mistakes," she said.
</P>
<P>
Neither side could gain an advantage in a tense first half.
</P>
<P>
In the 28th minute, Zhao Lihong got a sight at goal after being
set up by Zhang Ouying, only to squander the best chance of the
game so far by shooting wide.
</P>
<P>
As halftime approached, a tackle by Lorrie Fair robbed Sun just
when it looked as though she had found a way through.
</P>
<P>
Good work from Slaton brought two chances for the United States
in as many minutes in the second half.
</P>
<P>
First her long cross presented Sindy Parlow with a clear header,
but the striker could only set the ball straight at goalkeeper Han
Wenxia.
</P>
<P>
Then Slaton was in action again, setting up the experienced Mia
Hamm who shot wide.
</P>
<P>
But it all came apart for Slaton when she pulled back Sun five
minutes from time to concede the match-winning penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
