<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Cyprus Parties Quarrel Over "Paramilitary Group" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A head-on clash between Cyprus'
ruling Democratic Rally (DISY) party and main opposition AKEL party
over the "paramilitary" issue is now becoming "an unending storm"
on the political arena of the island.
</P>
<P>
The row started on Friday, when AKEL deputy Costas Papacostas
charged that DISY was harbouring a clandestine paramilitary group
to keep tabs on the political opinions of officers in the National
Guard, Cyprus' armed forces.
</P>
<P>
"The aim of the paramilitary staff is to monitor National Guard
activities and record the political beliefs of Cypriot officers,
classifying them into friends, foes, and the dangerous," he said.
</P>
<P>
Papacostas said he had documents naming well-known DISY
supporters as members of the group.
</P>
<P>
But DISY vehemently denied the allegations, accusing Papacostas
of having "ulterior political motives."
</P>
<P>
The allegations are being investigated both by the defense
ministry and the police. Defense Minister Socratis Hasikos said he
had ordered Evangelos Florakis, chief of National Guard, to
investigate the allegations and report to him on June 5.
</P>
<P>
But Florakis, a retired Greek general who took the post of
National Guard Chief earlier this month, appeared to give credence
to the accusations.
</P>
<P>
He said he had seen documents relating to an alleged
paramilitary group and that they were "serious."
</P>
<P>
"I almost fell off my chair... I said this would have to be
investigated or I would resign," he said at an emergency meeting
called by the Defense Committee of the parliament to discuss the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The army chief also confirmed that some officers had come
forward to testify in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former National Guard Chief General Demetrios Demou
distanced himself from the spat.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Demou said he knew nothing about any
such group and that no one had ever given him any documents
concerning its existence.
</P>
<P>
Hasikos, a former DISY deputy, told the defense committee his
ministry "never felt the presence of paramilitary groups in its
workings."
</P>
<P>
He vowed to come down hard on anyone found guilty of intervening
in army affairs.
</P>
<P>
President Glafcos Clerides has called both AKEL and DISY to calm
down over the issue, in view of the upcoming United Nations-
sponsored proximity talks on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Michalis Papapetrou also issued a plea for
a "dampening of tones" in the clash.
</P>
<P>
Despite the government plea for calm, the row is raging both in
and outside the parliamentary defense committee, without signs of
compromise from either side.
</P>
<P>
DISY leader Nicos Anastassiades threatened to reveal documents
proving that the left-wing AKEL had received funding from an
undisclosed foreign secret service if AKEL continued its assault.
</P>
<P>
AKEL spokesman Nicos Katsourides repulsed the allegation by
saying that Anastassiades was trying to divert the public from the
real issue, which was the existence of a group with the aim to
restrict the authority of the commander of the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that DISY was harbouring fascists, adding that
active army officers were not allowed to be party members or open
supporters.
</P>
<P>
Petros Clerides, deputy attorney-general, said that a criminal
inquiry could probe deeper into the allegations because of the
powers given by law to the attorney general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
