<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat's Advisor Denies Restart of Final Status Talks on Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian-Israeli final-status
negotiations will not be resumed on Wednesday as previously agreed,
said Nabil Abu Rdeineh, advisor to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio announced on Tuesday that the talks would be
resumed on Wednesday and would be moved from Stockholm to the
region.
</P>
<P>
Abu Rdeineh said the resumption of negotiations will be
discussed during a meeting of the Palestinian negotiating committee
to be held later in the day under the chairmanship of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital will be
declared on September 13, said Abu Rdeineh, adding that Israel has
to pull out from all the West Bank and Gaza in accordance with
United Nations Resolution 242.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to find a swift solution to the issue of the
Palestinian prisoners in order to create a proper atmosphere for
the resumption of the talks, Abu Rdeineh added.
</P>
<P>
The final-status talks touch upon the thorniest issues between
the two sides, including Jerusalem, border, Palestinian refugees,
Jewish settlements, security and water.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Arab East Jerusalem in 1967 and declare the
whole Jerusalem its eternal and indivisible capital, while the
Palestinians want East Jerusalem for their future independent
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
