<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Becomes Center to Mark No Tobacco Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Chosen by the World Health
Organization (WHO), Thailand on Wednesday became the center to
commemorate this year's World No Tobacco Day, which falls on May
31.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony held here to mark the event Wednesday, visiting
WHO chief Gro Harlem Brundtland conferred an honorable plate on
King of Thailand Bhumibol Adulyade for successfully leading the
country to control tobacco consumption.
</P>
<P>
During the ceremony, The Thai Public Health Ministry also
presented the king with a petition, which contains over one
million names of Thai people nationwide and pledges to stop
smoking,.
</P>
<P>
Beginning Wednesday, Various activities marking the World No
Tobacco Day are being held here and will continue till Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A poll conducted by Assumption Business Administration
University here recently found that 79.9 percent of respondents do
not smoke, while 63.6 percent of those who smoke said that they
intended to quit smoking on the World No Tobacco Day.
</P>
<P>
Most respondents also agreed with the government's recent all-
out ban on broadcasting smoking behaviors, and expressed their
support for a move to ban imported cigarettes and strict measures
to curb smoking among teenagers and youths, according to the poll.
</P>
</TEXT>
