<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambicans Agree on Minimum Price for Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Cotton Institute
(IAM), the cotton companies, and representatives of associations
of peasant producers have agreed on a minimum price of 2,500
meticais (16 U.S. cents) a kilo for raw cotton in the coming
harvest, reports Wednesday's issue of the independent news sheet
"Metical".
</P>
<P>
In nominal terms, this is an increase of 200 meticais a kilo
on last years price of 2,300 meticais, a rise of 9 percent.
However, over the same period the meticais has devalued sharply
against the U.S. dollar. When it was introduced in mid-1999, the
price of 2,300 meticais was equivalent to over 18 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The companies protested that even with a producer price of
2,300 meiticais a kilo, they made a loss when they exported the
cotton. In 1999, world cotton price slumped to their lowest level
in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the price is improving, and on Tuesday stood at
61.55 cents a kilo. But "Metical" points out that there is no
guarantee that the price will not slip again later in the year.
</P>
<P>
In any case, the price is still a long way short of the 70 or
80 cents a kilo that cotton was fetching on the world market in
the mid 1990s. High international prices made possible a minimum
producer price of 3,300 meiticais a kilo, for top grade cotton, in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Currently cotton is the only crop for which the government,
through the IAM, sets a minimum producer price. But this is likely
to disappear in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's meeting between the IAM, the companies and the
associations, there was general consensus that the liberalization
of the sector was " irreversible".
</P>
<P>
A working group has been set up to look at the entire cotton
sector, and will draw up proposals for altering the rules for
cotton marketing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
