<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- The Omani government has approved in principle the
construction of the Middle East largest ammonia and urea complex.
The complex will be built in the Sahar Industrial Zone and is
expected to start operation in 2004. The daily production has been
set at 2,000 tons of ammonia and 2,600 tons of urea.
</P>
<P>
The duration of the project building ranges between 30 and 33
months and will start in the first half of next year. The tender
date will be announced before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The production will be targeting the markets of Asia, Europe and
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The International Company for Fish Farming (ASMAC)
in Abu Dhabi announced on Tuesday the establishment of two new
branches in Kuwait and Oman. The move is part of the company's
future plan to expand the scope of its activities in fish farming
to cover the local and regional needs and export the surplus in the
following years to Europe.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Al-Khaleej Fish Farming Company is taking
place in cooperation with Kuwaiti partners with ASMAC having 49
percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
ASMAC has also bought 65 percent of the capital of Qurayat
company which it established with the Omani Zawbaa company.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's first domestically manufactured passenger
plane "Iran-140" will be test-flied by the end of September,
Defense Minister Ali Shamkhani said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-140 plane has a capacity of some 50 passengers and can
fly up to an altitude of about 7,600 meters with a speed of 575
kilometers per hour and its flight range is 2,100 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Shamkhani cited low fuel consumption, low engine noise and
maneuverability as the main features of the plane.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait and Jordan initialed Tuesday an agreement
on avoiding double taxation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Finance Assistant Undersecretary Fawzi Al-Qassar, who
signed the deal on behalf of the Kuwaiti side, said that under the
agreement, the Kuwaiti government and its establishments are to be
exempted from taxes on share profits and loan interest while other
investors will have to pay a 5-percent tax.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official said the deal applies a 30-percent tax on
patents and literary, scientific and commercial copyrights.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also includes terms of tax exemption on salaries
and bonuses of diplomats and employees of Kuwait Airways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
