<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Price Increase to impact on African States' Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) has said that although the global economy
grew during 1999, the economies of sub-Saharan African countries
grew by a lower rate compared with 1998, Times of Zambia newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A COMESA annual report just released said the increase in oil
prices and adverse climatic conditions will affect the performance
and growth of sub- Saharan economies this year and next year.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Saharan economies, excluding Nigeria and South Africa,
recorded an average growth rate of 3.2 percent last year compared
with 3.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to COMESA estimates, although the 3.2 percent growth
rate may appear reasonable, it was insufficient to raise per
capita Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for the sub-Saharan countries.
</P>
<P>
The effects of war in various parts of the continent has been
cited as the major contributing factor to the hindrance of
economic growth on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"Prospects for the current year and the year 2001 are rather
mixed as oil prices rise and adverse climatic conditions, notably
flooding and drought, affect the region variably," the report
adds.
</P>
<P>
COMESA is optimistic however that the continued pursuit of
sustainable open, market- oriented economy and good governance
policies is likely to have a positive effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Implement Zero Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia Revenue Authority (ZRA)
will strictly implement the zero tariff under the Common Market
for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to match tariffs from
other member countries, a senior official of ZRA has said.
</P>
<P>
Nathan Chishimaba, ZRA head of executive support unit, was
quoted by Wednesday's Times of Zambia newspaper as saying that the
COMESA Free Trade Area (FTA) scheduled for October 31 this year
will be effected on an automated system for customs data system by
changing the configuration that calculates duty at a preferential
rate.
</P>
<P>
About 13 countries in the COMESA region are operating the
system and ZRA is currently working to upgrade the system to
achieve the advanced automated system for customs data, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The implementation of zero tariffs will be done on a strictly
reciprocal basis. This means that concessions will be offered only
to the extent that various member countries will apply import
tariffs to exports originating from Zambia," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the Zambian authority had put in place an
audit and business risk department at the customs head office to
look at post- clearance of goods.
</P>
<P>
There was also a control unit at the customs head office called
outfield that consists of officers trained in enforcement and
investigations which would monitor transactions in all major
border stations, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Chishimaba, the operations of the outfield
officers would be backed by an intensive data monitoring and
exchange program with other countries in COMESA to ensure that the
rules of origin are verified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Calls for Action to Save Wild Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
has called for decisive action to save the wild Atlantic salmon
from distinction.
</P>
<P>
"More than 300 rivers have already lost their wild salmon
stocks, and each year more rivers lose their salmon or show signs
of rapidly decreasing spawning populations," WWF's Henning Roed
said Wednesday as government representatives gathered in Canada
this week in the lead-up to the 17th North Atlantic Salmon
Conservation Organization (NASCO) meeting.
</P>
<P>
The causes of the decline are diverse but they are all man-made,
said Roed, who is coordinating the WWF's research. Dams and other
river engineering works block the salmon's passage to suitable
spawning grounds. Industrial domestic and agricultural pollution
destroys clean habitats. Farmed salmon, of which almost a million
escape each year in Norway alone, are a risk to wild salmon
because they spread diseases and parasites that can kill wild
populations.
</P>
<P>
New WWF research shows that stocks of this species have plunged
to their lowest ever levels. The wild Atlantic salmon, which
spawns in freshwater but spends much of its life at sea, could be
bound for extinction if current trends continue, according to the
WWF.
</P>
<P>
In North America, the number of large salmon returning to their
native rivers has dropped by 90 percent; the species has
disappeared from more than three quarters of Baltic rivers in the
last 100 years; and catches of salmon in Scotland and Ireland are
down to roughly 25 percent of what they were three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
"NASCO countries must institute catch limits based on
scientific recommendations, and close mixed-salmon fisheries that
adversely affect endangered salmon stocks," said Roed. "It's vital
for them to adopt standards for responsible salmon fish farming
that stop its negative impact on wild stocks, and to oppose the
introduction of genetically modified salmon." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
