<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lobbying Intensifies for Turkey's Attack Helicopter Tender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- As Turkey's multi-billion-dollar
attack helicopter bid approached its end on Friday, competing
countries have increased their lobbying activities for the project.
</P>
<P>
Following Russian Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov's visit,
Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sne also came to Ankara to
push for the joint Russian-Israeli Erdogan helicopter company in
the bid, Turkish Daily News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov visited Ankara last week and delivered Russian
President Vladimir Putin's letter to Turkish President Ahmet Sezer
in which Putin reportedly asked for Sezer's support in the attack
helicopter project.
</P>
<P>
The tender envisages Turkey's co-production of 145 helicopters
with the bid winner, including an initial batch of 50 helicopters
for the Turkish Armed Forces (TSK).
</P>
<P>
The bid is expected to cost a total of 2 billion U.S. dollars.
Turkey had postponed its final decision, for the third time, on the
selection of the bid winner because some companies have not offered
the requested export license with their bid.
</P>
<P>
After eliminating French company Eurocopter's Tiger and U.S.
company Boeing's AH-64D Apache Longbow, the remaining three bidders
include Russian company Kamov with Israeli company IAI's KA-50/52
Erdogan, Italian company Agusta's A129-I and U.S. company Bell
Helicopter-Textron's AH-IZ King Cobra.
</P>
<P>
So far, Russia's Kamov has presented a letter of assurance for
export clearance. However, it was speculated that if Turkey selects
the King Cobra, the U.S. Congress may facilitate authorization of
an export license.
</P>
<P>
Drawing attention to close Turkish-Israeli relations, some
sources said the joint Russian-Israeli company may have a chance of
winning the bid because of its low cost and Israeli promise to
transfer high technology to Turkey in the manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has
called Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit to solicit his support
in the tender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
