<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Sends Observer Team to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A six-member advance team of
Commonwealth observers has been deployed in Zimbabwe ahead of next
month's parliamentary elections in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Tuesday, the Commonwealth Secretariat
office in Harare said the group arrived in the country at the
weekend and was deployed after briefings.
</P>
<P>
The team is part of the 44 observers during the June 24 and 25
elections. Other members will arrive in the country next month.
</P>
<P>
"The formation of a Commonwealth Observer Group for the
Zimbabwe elections followed discussions between Commonwealth
Secretary-General Don Mckinnon and Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe in Harare earlier this month," said the Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, its assessment mission showed that
there was broad support within Zimbabwe for the presence of
Commonwealth observers during the polls.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the European Union reportedly confirmed on Tuesday
that it will send 160 observers to Zimbabwe to monitor the June 24
and 25 elections.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has been gripped by a wave of political violence with
at least 20 people having been killed so far in the run-up to
parliamentary elections to be held on June 24 and 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
