<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Coffee Production Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's coffee output is
expected to reach 50,000 tons this year, which represents an
increase of 12,000 tons within three years.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's Financial Times Wednesday quoted the Tanzania Coffee
Board (TCB) Managing Director Leslie Omari as saying that they are
implementing projects aimed at producing 60,000 tons of coffee by
the year 2003, and 70, 000 tons by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
He said all stakeholders in the coffee industry, the Coffee
Management Unit, cooperative unions, private companies and the
coffee governing board have joined a campaign to revive coffee
production.
</P>
<P>
Under the campaign, which started about three years ago,
strategies were put in place to avail about 16 million coffee
seedlings to farmers to replace aging trees.
</P>
<P>
Coffee has been the major export in Tanzania's foreign trade
for the last two to three decades. Unlike other exports,
Tanzania's coffee remains a hot cake in the international markets
and over 98 percent of its total crop is exported.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued recently by the TCB, Germany
maintains its position as Tanzania's number one coffee export
market followed by Japan, the Netherlands, Belgium, Spain and
Italy.
</P>
<P>
Germany dominated 38 percent of Tanzanian total coffee exports,
followed by Japan with 18 percent, the Netherlands 14 percent and
Belgium 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
