<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Sells State-Owned Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The German-led consortium that won
the bid to buy majority shares in Uganda Telecom Limited (UTL) has
paid 33.5 million U.S. dollars for the 51 percent of stake in the
state-owned company, the New Vision daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The consortium, led by Detecon Gmbh and Telecel International
of Switzerland, made the payment Tuesday, six days to the June 5
deadline set by the Ugandan government.
</P>
<P>
Peter Sommer, Detecon's head of telecommunications department
for Africa, handed over the bank draft to Ugandan Finance Minister
Gerald Ssendaula in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
Orascom, a leading telecommunication firm in Egypt, has also
joined the venture.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be sealed on Friday with the signing of the
agreement to hand over UTL to the new buyers, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"The closing of this transaction will mark the full
liberalization of Uganda's telecommunications sector," Michael
Opagi, Ugandan Privatization Unit director, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The government will continue to hold a 49-percent stake in
UTL, which is expected to be sold to the public at the earliest
opportunity on the Uganda Stock Exchange," Opagi said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Ssendaula said it is government policy to
liberalize all public utilities.
</P>
<P>
The bid-winner consortium is supposed to install 100,000 fixed
lines within the next five years in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
Ssendaula expressed the hope that the consortium will also
extend services to the countryside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
