<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Parents Expect Children to Win High Degrees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey shows that one-
fourth of Chinese parents would like their children to earn
advanced degrees, while 36 percent would be satisfied if their
kids can get at least undergraduate diplomas.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted among young parents in Beijing,
Shanghai, Guangzhou and Chongqing, which are all major big cities
in China. Results of the survey indicated that parents have much
higher expectation for their children than ten years ago,
according to China Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that 22.7 percent of the parents want their
children to become involved in high-tech-related jobs which need
professional skills or to become officials.
</P>
<P>
Some 17.5 percent of parents would like their children to be
employees in government organizations, compared with only 3.5
percent ten years ago. Those who hope their children will become
workers, clerks in companies, and primary and middle school
teachers accounted for just ten percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with ten years ago, parents spend more money on books
and toys for their children but take less time to read stories and
sing songs to them, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
The education level of mothers has a great impact on children's
growth, it found. The survey showed that mothers with higher
degrees tend to make more intelligent evaluations of their
children. For example, 34.3 percent of mothers who have a college
education said that the most promising quality of their children
is common sense; the statistic is 10 percent higher than among
mothers with middle and high school education.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-one percent of parents said they do not have enough time
to spend with their kids, 38 percent don't think they have good
parenting skills, while only four percent blame poor environment
and financial woes for their problems with their children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
