<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets World Records in Carbon Fiber Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) have succeeded in producing the world's thinnest
carbon nanotubes, a type of carbon fiber.
</P>
<P>
A research group headed by Xie Sishen, a research professor
with the Institute of Physics under the CAS, has developed carbon
nanotubes which are only 0.5 nanometers in diameter.
</P>
<P>
This is very near the theoretical limit, which is 0.4
nanometers, said Professor Xie. Before his achievement, the
thinnest carbon nanotube in the world was 0.7 nanometers in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
One nanometer is only one/one-billionth of a meter. But carbon
nanotubes with so thin a diameter have great potential for use in
microelectronics.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have found that the thinner a carbon tube is, the
more stable its molecular structure becomes. Therefore, they
attempt to control the molecular structure of carbon nanotubes by
narrowing their diameter, and this will help promote research in
the application of such material.
</P>
<P>
The results of Professor Xie's studies were published in the
January 27 edition of "Nature," the leading English science
magazine.
</P>
<P>
Professor Xie and his research team shattered the world record
by developing the longest carbon nanometer in 1998. They are
currently experimenting with more accurate measurements of carbon
nanometers, and other aspects to consolidate their findings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
