<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli settlement leaders expressed alarm Tuesday at reports
that Israel has agreed to grant the Palestinians the control of 92
percent of the West Bank, including the Jordan Valley settlements,
during the recent "back-channel" talks in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Jewish Communities in Judea, Samaria and Gaza
(the West Bank and Gaza Strip) has called on settlers throughout
the territories to attend an emergency meeting Wednesday evening to
discuss the issues and decide on protest action.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan Valley settlers are to launch their own
protest campaign. The 4,000 Jewish residents of the Jordan Valley
and Megillot regional councils were surprised by the reports,
having always believed their communities were part of the Israeli
consensus.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israel Defense Forces will soon embark on a stringent new
program to fight drug abuse among its troops, with the goal of
testing every soldier at least once in his three-year service.
</P>
<P>
IDF investigations of soldiers being released from service in
recent years show a substantial rise in the number of soldiers
taking drugs. The average age at which the soldiers first take
drugs is just over 17, about a year before their induction into
military service.
</P>
<P>
Drug-related disciplinary action files on soldiers who have sold
or abused drugs (mostly marijuana and Ecstasy) also continue to
rise.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk said Tuesday that his
country expects Syria to withdraw its military forces from Lebanon
following Israel's withdrawal from the security zone last week.
</P>
<P>
Indyk promised while on a tour of Metulla, that the United
States would provide Israel with aid to assist in the redeployment
of IDF troops along the international border.
</P>
<P>
He said that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright promised
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak that the U.S. would release 50
million U.S. dollars to finance the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and U.S. President Bill
Clinton are to meet in Germany on Thursday to discuss prospects for
peace with Syria and Lebanon after the Israeli troops' withdrawal,
as well as the bogged Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had hoped for a breakthrough in the Palestinian track
before the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, and now Barak wants to
coordinate positions with Clinton as the negotiations with the
Palestinians move to a critical stage, said a source in Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
