<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Give Bangladesh Grant for Polio Eradication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Japan will provide 9 million U.S.
dollars to Bangladesh for polio vaccines and programs related to
supplementary immunization in the country under an agreement
signed between Japan and the United Nations Children's Fund on
behalf of Bangladesh in Dhaka, the Daily Star reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be utilized to procure 90 million doses of polio
vaccines to immunize about 21 million children under five in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Japan is the single largest donor in this regard and it has
borne almost 50 percent of the total cost for the supplementary
immunization in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Japan started supporting Bangladesh for polio eradication in
1996, and has already provided a total of 27.5 million dollars for
implementation of its national immunization program.
</P>
<P>
Extraordinary progress has been achieved globally for polio
eradication, and the number of known polio-endemic countries
dropped from 50 in 1998 to 30 last year.
</P>
<P>
In Bangladesh, polio cases have been reduced by 87 percent due
to its supplementary immunization program. However, it is still
among the 30 remaining countries in the world where polio is
endemic.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Health and Family Welfare Chowdhury reiterated
the need for continued support from donors till the country wins
the battle against polio virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
