<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Attaining Yearly Growth Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Despite the slightly lower than
expected economic expansion in the first quarter, the Philippine
government said Wednesday that it remains confident its overall
growth targets for 2000 are still attainable.
</P>
<P>
Director General Felipe Medalla of the National Economic and
Development Authority said the recent positive developments in the
political front in Mindanao would help speed up he government's
economic recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth for the first quarter, measured through the
gross national product, registered at 3.45 percent, which is less
than the four to five percent growth target set by the government
for this year.
</P>
<P>
"If we can recover in the second semester, we can still achieve
our four percent goal," Medalla said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
Medalla said the government expects the rebound of the
agriculture sector during the subsequent months to spur growth.
The farm sector posted a growth rate of only 0.2 percent for the
January-March period.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Mdalla said the recovery of the peso and the growth
of the economy are back on track, especially now that the worst of
the Mindanao conflict appears to have ended as shown by the
resumption of the peace talks between the government and the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
He said the government still expects economic growth to reach
four percent this year, contrary to the reported analyses of
economists that growth targets may go down to two percent.
</P>
<P>
Medalla noted that the stock market appears upbeat with news
about the resumption of the peace negotiations with the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front, along with the ongoing talks for the
release of the 21 hostages in Sulu province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
