<HEADLINE> 1stlead: Fiji's Army Chief Says He Will Be President: ABC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's army Commander Frank
Bainimarama said on Wednesday that he will serve as Fiji's
president for two to three years, the Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC) said.
</P>
<P>
The ABC quoted Bainimarama as saying that it will take that
long to draw up a new constitution and prepare for elections in
the Pacific nation.
</P>
<P>
He said he will be president, and former military chief Ratu
Epeli Nailatikau will be prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama said Ratu Epeli was talking to people with no
political affiliations about becoming ministers, the ABC reported.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was prepared to give an amnesty to coup leader
George Speight and six of his men, even though they had taken over
Parliament and seized hostages.
</P>
<P>
But he said the amnesty will not cover the murder of a
policeman in the capital Suva on last Sunday night or the attack
on Fiji's television headquarters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
