<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy Envoy to Chechnya Killed in Grozny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government's deputy
envoy to Chechnya and an assistant mayor of Grozny, capital of the
breakaway province, were killed Tuesday evening in a mine
explosion, the Interfax news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Sergei Zverev, the deputy envoy, and Nurseda
Khabuseyeva, the assistant mayor, died at about 6:30 p.m. local
time (0230 GMT) when their car was hit by two remote-controlled
landmines and came under automatic gun fire along a road linking
Grozny and Urus-Martan.
</P>
<P>
The mayor of Grozny, Supyan Mokhchayev, who was riding in the
same vehicle, was injured in the attack, Interfax reported,
quoting the Russian Interior Ministry's office for Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Mokhchayev was listed in a "moderately serious" condition. He
suffered a head injury.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have launched investigation into the attack and
the federal envoy to Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, flew from Moscow
to the scene of the crime early Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
