<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landslide Rescue Reports Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TANGMAI, May 31 (Xinhua) -- After days of toil, emergency
workers in Tibet have removed a substantial chunk of a wall of mud
and rock formed during a landslide at Yigong Township in Tibet
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Officers and men of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA)
along with local residents have moved 1.31 million cubic meters of
mud from the mound, which stemmed the flow of the Yigong River,
bringing the water level at Yigong down by 21 meters.
</P>
<P>
Workers also have opened up a 38-km stretch of road linking the
Sichuan-Tibet highway with the affected area at Yiyong and built a
600-meter overhead cable to ensure transport of relief materials.
</P>
<P>
The PLA has sent to Yigong 200 motor vehicles and 600 officers
and soldiers who worked there day and night. The army also has
shipped 150 tons of relief materials to Yigong and moved 1,200
sick and old residents out of the affected area.
</P>
<P>
"PLA soldiers and armed policemen are stationed where there are
hardships and danger. Their energetic support led to the speedy
recovery at Yigong," said Gyapo, vice-chairman of the regional
government.
</P>
<P>
A rare landslide followed by mud and rock flows pelted Yigong
Township of Bomi County on the evening of April 9. About 300
million cubic meters of mud and rock temporarily dammed the Yigong
River, destroying seven kilometers of highways, submerging large
tracts of cropland and tea plantations, and leaving more than 4,
000 local people homeless.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
