<HEADLINE> Living Conditions of Chinese Children Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The living conditions of Chinese
children have improved during the past ten years due to the
country's hard efforts, according to the All-China Women's
Federation (ACWF).
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Chinese government already fulfilled
some goals of the Development Program for Chinese Children in the
1990s ahead of the schedule, the Workers' Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate among children under five years of age
dropped to 39.1 per thousand in 1999, 0.15 percent lower than the
goal set by the program.
</P>
<P>
The mortality rate among pregnant and lying-in women also fell
to 59.1 per 100,000, a drop of 7.1 percent compared with a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
China has speeded up the utilization of sanitary toilet
facilities vital to rural people's health, and such facilities are
now available for 35.03 percent of the rural population.
</P>
<P>
Central Finance will grant 50 million yuan this year and next
to lower the mortality rate of pregnant and lying-in women and
eliminate tetanus in 378 poor counties in northwest and southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
The Working Commission for Women and Children of the State
Council will inspect the implementation of this program in the
second half of this year to promote the protection of women and
children's rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
