<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Advance Team in Pyongyang for Inter-Korean Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 31 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's advance team left for
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) Wednesday through
the truce village of Panmunjom to prepare for inter-Korean summit
on June 12-14 in Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
The 30-member team, led by Son In-kyo, a director-general of
the Unification Ministry, will stay in Pyongyang until June 12 to
wrap up preparations for the summit between President Kim Dae-jung
and DPRK leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
Son said the team would make every effort to guarantee the
smooth progress of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The team will consult with DPRK officials to work out an agenda
and decide how many times the two leaders would meet as well as
security, protocol and communications matters.
</P>
<P>
Upon its arrival in Pyongyang, the team has opened up five
direct phone lines with Seoul and the number is expected to reach
50 when the summit starts.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first ever inter-Korean summit since the Korean
peninsula was divided half a century ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
