<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers Stay Alive With Away Win Over Lakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Portland Trail Blazers stayed
alive Tuesday night in the Western Conference finals with a 96-88
victory over the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
Injured veteran Scottie Pippen managed 22 points, six steals
and four blocked shots, breaking Michael Jordan's playoff record
of 376 steals with 380.
</P>
<P>
With his team facing elimination, Pippen took complete control
in a terrific all-around performance. The versatile forward was
everywhere, running the offense while making three-pointers and
drives and spearheading the defense with blocks, steals and a
thorough shutdown of Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
Rasheed Wallace was just 7-for-21 from the field, but scored 22
points, including seven of eight free throws, and grabbed 10
rebounds. Steve Smith added 13 points, and Arvydas Sabonis 12.
Brian Grant and Detlef Schrempf added nine each.
</P>
<P>
The Blazers never trailed, jumping out to an early lead for the
third straight game. Unlike Games Three and Four at home, when
they suffered through second-half collapses, the Blazers surged in
the third quarter and temporarily denied Los Angeles its first
trip to the NBA Finals since 1991 with a homecourt victory.
</P>
<P>
Shaquille O'Neal did his best to make it the big night everyone
expected with 31 points and 21 rebounds. Ron Harper added 14
points.
</P>
<P>
But Kobe Bryant made only four of 13 shots, scored 17 points
and committed six turnovers before fouling out with 4:45 to play.
Glen Rice was 1-for-8 from the field and 0-for-5 from 3-point
range, finishing with four points.
</P>
<P>
With Los Angeles up 3-2, the series shift back to Portland for
Game 6 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Since both competing teams in the Eastern Conference finals,
the Indiana Pacers and New York Knicks do not match up well
against the Lakers, many experts tabbed the Western Conference
finals as the real championship confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
