<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Young Shuttlers Vow to Join Thomas Cup Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's victory of bringing
home the Thomas Cup four consecutive times has motivated young
shuttlers to follow in their seniors' steps, according to the
Jakarta Post Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ronny Agustinus said that he wanted to join the Thomas Cup team
in the upcoming two years.
</P>
<P>
"I have realized that I have yet to reach my best achievement
in international tournaments. But I hope to improve my physical
condition and mentality in the future to follow in my seniors'
steps," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ronny, 22, said he always had psychological problems in
international tournaments, especially when competing in major
events and facing tough opponents.
</P>
<P>
"I have discussed how to overcome my psychological barrier with
coach Agus Dwi Santoso. I also have problems in improving my
concentration on the court. But I prefer to talk to my coach
instead of psychologists," he added.
</P>
<P>
Teammate Johan Hadikusuma shared the same idea of joining the
next Thomas Cup team.
</P>
<P>
"I don't have any experience in competing in a team event but
in the next two years I must be able to replace the seniors on the
Thomas Cup team," said Johan, who is a younger brother to the 1992
Olympic Games gold medalist Alan Budikusuma.
</P>
<P>
Both Ronny and Johan said the presence of physical trainer
Ridwan Soemardjo helped them to increase their fitness.
</P>
<P>
"But I hope the trainer and the coach can discuss about the
training program more intensively to reach the maximum performance
in the future," Ronny said.
</P>
<P>
"Should the Badminton Association of Indonesia want to have a
physical trainer, they must do it continuously, not only for a
short term period as they did with the Thomas Cup team," Johan
said.
</P>
<P>
If the singles expressed their high motivation, the doubles
specialist Ade Lukas, partnering with Santoso Sugihardjo, seemed
pessimistic on his chance to join the next team.
</P>
<P>
"The competition in the doubles sector is much tougher compared
to the singles. We still have many good young doubles, including
Candra Wijaya and Tony Gunawan; Flandy Limpele and Eng Hian; and
Halim Heryanto and Sigit Budiarto. It's really hard for us to
compete against them. But we are trying," he said.
</P>
<P>
All players said they wanted to achieve better in the upcoming
four tournaments: the Indonesian Open, Malaysia Open, Thailand
Open and Singapore Open.
</P>
<P>
"I want to win one of the four tournaments titles," said Johan,
while Ronny said he wanted to upset the seeds at the event.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
