<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji: Military Action Against Hostagetakers Ruled out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fiji's military head Commodore Frank Bainimarama said
negotiations were still continuing to try to win the release of
the toppled Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry and his fellow
hostages, held at the parliament house since May 19.
</P>
<P>
He said that a military action is not an option "right now" and
"We have to think of the lives of the hostages - we want to
continue dialogue."
</P>
<P>
According to Radio Fiji, Speight was refusing to accept any
appointment unless he and his supporters are "properly consulted."
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama said Fiji's 1997 constitution had been torn up and
may not be rewritten for anything up to three years, the AAP
reported.
</P>
<P>
Bainimarama ruled out any possibility that Mahendra Chaudhry
would return to his post. "I am afraid Mahendra Chaudhry will not
come back as prime minister," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Bainimarama appointed former military commander and
diplomat Ratu Epeli Nailatikau to head an interim council of
ministers.
</P>
<P>
As for President Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, who stepped down on
Monday night, Bainimarama said he "does not want to come back."
</P>
<P>
In Suva, the capital of Fiji, Speight's supporters began
hijacking vehicles and beating up drivers Wednesday as Tuesday
night's negotiations between the military and Speight failed to
reach a result, the AAP reported.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in the capital rose dramatically Wednesday morning
with taxis driven by ethnic Indian drivers being stopped, and
Speight's supporters took control of roads around the parliament
house compound, where 30 hostages are held, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
