<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grenade Explosion Kills Two in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Following bomb blasts in Medan,
capital of Indonesia's North Sumatra province, a grenade exploded
in Nganjuk of East Java province on Tuesday, killing two people
and injuring two others, reports reaching here Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
A police officer said the grenade exploded at 11:30 a.m. (local
time) on Jl. Gatot Subroto close to the Nganjuk bus station. The
blast also caused traffic jam in the area.
</P>
<P>
The police also found several other grenades, an M-16 rifle and
FN pistol near to the spot where the grenade exploded, said the
reports.
</P>
<P>
Separately, a fifth explosive device in three days found in
North Sumatra was discovered at dawn on Tuesday near to the Trans
Sumatra Highway in Lubuk Pakam, Deli Serdang, about 28 kilometers
northeast of Medan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, following the string of incidents, North Sumatra
Police chief Brig. Gen. Sutanto asked preachers to calm the
situation, noting that North Sumatra is commonly used as a
barometer for inciting riots in the country and pointed to
incidents in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure, with adequate awareness and faith, we can safeguard
our territory from provocateurs," Sutanto was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The North Sumatra province has been rocked by a spate of bomb
attacks. On Sunday a bomb exploded in a church, injuring 47 people.
Two other bombs which did not detonate were discovered in two
other churches.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, another blast took place in front of a restaurant,
injuring three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
