<HEADLINE> Drug-related Crimes Rise in Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh First Deputy Prime Minister
Alexander Pavlov Tuesday called on local governments to fight
drug-related crimes as their priority.
</P>
<P>
Pavlov said in Astana, capital of Kazakhstan, that drug-related
crimes rose sharply in the first four months. Of the more than 46,
000 criminal cases reported in the period, one sixth was related
with drug.
</P>
<P>
Pavlov told an anti-drug forum that the number of teenager drug
addicts increased by 4.7 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Kazakh officials attributed the increase to the rise of drug
trafficking from Southeast Asian countries and Afghanistan and the
growth of a large amount of drug plants in Chuya valley.
</P>
<P>
Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev signed an order in mid-
May to work out a policy of combating drug addiction and
trafficking in 2000-2005. 
</P>
