<HEADLINE> Small Changes in Daily Habits Bring Huge Business (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Coca Cola has invested more than 1.1 billion U.S. dollars in
China, and now occupies 33 percent of the country's carbonated
beverage market.
</P>
<P>
A survey shows an average Chinese drink an average of seven
bottles of Coca Cola's products a year, much less than the 395
bottles consumed on average by Americans. This means the market in
China still has huge potential.
</P>
<P>
Other successful U.S. companies which have done well bringing
Western drinks and food to Chinese include Pepsi Cola, Kentucky
Fried Chicken (KFC), and McDonald's. KFC has opened more than 300
outlets across the country, all of which are making money.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Bell, a Sino-Belgian joint venture, now controls one-
third of China's program-controlled telephone exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Other overseas companies such as Motorola, Ericsson, Nokia, and
Samsung have also realized profits by investing in
telecommunications in China.
</P>
<P>
Motorola has so far invested 1.5 billion US dollars, and earned
nearly 3.1 billion U.S. dollars in sales in China last year.
</P>
<P>
The Internet has also witnessed a speedy development in China,
and the number of people now on-line has surpassed 10 million, and
is expected to double in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Insiders say that China is expected to become one of the world'
s largest e-commerce markets when its traditional industries go on-
line for information, management, and sales services.
</P>
<P>
New trends have also swept such fields as computer, automobiles,
clothing, medicine, and cosmetics, creating a huge and varied
market for both Chinese and overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Doctor Tao says entrepreneurs will find their way to fortune as
they get to know the changing living and consumption habits in
modern China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
