<HEADLINE> Canadian Provinces Urge Federal Health Care Allocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Canada's provincial health ministers
said Tuesday that they will discuss reforms of the health care
system only after an immediate federal injection of 4.5 billion
Canadian dollars (3 billion U.S. dollars) for provincial health
care and social programs.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting opening Tuesday in Quebec City, Quebec Health
Minister Pauline Marois said the injection could restore transfer
payments from the federal government to provincial health care and
social programs to a level of five years ago.
</P>
<P>
"After that, we'll discuss what could interest the provinces in
other areas concerning health," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian federal government has promised long-term funding
on condition that the provinces agree to map out a plan of reforms
with Federal Health Minister Allan Rock.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time the provincial health ministers have met
to discuss an agreement on health. They met with Rock months ago,
but failed to reach any deal because of the same differences,
where Rock insisted on a reform plan first, while his provincial
counterparts put more federal cash at the top place.
</P>
<P>
In a 62-page "cost-drivers" document presented to the meeting,
the provincial ministers said, "Canada's publicly funded health
care system is not in crisis, but the cost pressures and
constraints on the system are real."
</P>
<P>
Provincial and territorial health expenditures will be 67
billion Canadian dollars (44.7 billion dollars) within five years
and almost 85 billion (56.7 billion dollars) within 10 years, as a
combined result of population growth, aging, inflation and rising
costs for current programs, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
