<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Changes in Daily Habits Bring Huge Business (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Sanxiao Group is not the only enterprise which has
benefited from the improving living standard of the Chinese people.
The huge market potential brought by the changes in daily life has
been eyed by overseas producers as well. Such brands as "Crest," "
Colgate", and "Signal," produced by the U.S.'s P&AMP;G and Colgate,
and Britain's Unilever are now widely known in China.
</P>
<P>
To meet the growing demand of the Chinese people, the U.S.'s
Colgate company has recently decided to invest 36 million U.S.
dollars, joining hands with Sanxiao Group to set up a joint
venture in Yangzhou producing dental care products and detergents.
</P>
<P>
Tao Siyan,China's first doctor of folklore and professor at
the Dongnan University in Jiangsu Province, says that changes in
living habits are certain to lead to the formation of new consumer
markets. For entrepreneurs to be successful, they must have deep
insight into these changes in order to grasp the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese, who are more aware of new consumption trends in
China, have benefited from their early entry into the China market.
</P>
<P>
Japanese took the lead and exported state-of-the-art TVs, video
cassette recorders, and cameras to China, and for a long time
Japanese-made items monopolized China's household appliance market,
so that subsequently a number of related joint ventures backed by
Japanese firms were established in China.
</P>
<P>
By October 1999, nine Japanese firms had invested in more than
50 household appliance companies in China, according to Beijing
Center of Japan External Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The great success of the Japanese aroused the attention of many
entrepreneurs in the U.S. and Europe, and they began to conduct
market research on the changing consumption habits in China,
especially in the areas of foods and hi-tech items.
</P>
<P>
The Coca Cola company made its debut in China as early as 1927.
In 1981, they set up their first bottling plant in the People's
Republic in Beijing. Today, Coca Cola has 24 plants in Chinese
Mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Changes in Daily Habits Bring Huge Business (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Yao Wangshi, an 80-year-old woman
in Shuangmiao Village in east China's Jiangsu Province, spent the
first 60 years of her life using only salty water to clean her
teeth.
</P>
<P>
Yao brushed her teeth for the first time only 20 years ago, she
said, because that was the first time she could afford dental care
products.
</P>
<P>
Yao regarded this change in daily habits as the result of
improving living standards, which were due to the introduction of
China's reform and opening-up policy in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
"Every adult and child in Shuangmiao Village brush their teeth
now," Yao said.
</P>
<P>
It took decades for Chinese people to gradually replace
traditional dental care methods with the use of toothbrushes and
toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
In China's infant and primary schools today, courses on oral
hygiene are among those required of everyone, and toothbrushes and
toothpaste are so common in both rural and urban areas that if
anyone fails to brush their teeth, they are usually perceived as
having poor hygiene habits.
</P>
<P>
This change in oral hygiene care has made it possible for the
establishment of the world's largest toothbrush manufacturer in
the city of Yangzhou in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The Sanxiao Group, a private business set up in 1989, turned
out one billion toothbrushes last year, earning 1.5 billion yuan
in output value. Sanxiao now has 72 percent of the toothbrush
market in China, and also exports its products to more than 50
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Han Guoping, president of the Sanxiao Group, says that the
decision to establish the group was based on estimates that
Chinese people will pay more attention to oral hygiene now that
they are living a better life.
</P>
<P>
In the market economy, the key for enterprise success is to
create new businesses to meet the potential demand of the changing
market, Han points out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
