<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, May 31 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Tuesday voiced its
welcome to the resumption of the proximity talks between Ethiopia
and Eritrea and expressed its strong support to the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) in its effort to find a peaceful solution
to the conflict in the Horn of Africa region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the
Security Council, Wang Yingfan of China, said, "Members of the
Council welcomed the resumption" of the peace talks held in
Algiers, capital of Algeria, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council expressed their strong support to the
efforts of the OAU in finding a peaceful solution of the conflict,
" the statement said. "Members of the Security Council called on
the parties to cease hostilities and concentrate on diplomatic
efforts to resolve their conflict." (UN--Horn of AFrica-OAU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Tuesday that the Rome
talks between Washington and Pyongyang were serious and
constructive and made progress.
</P>
<P>
The six-day long talks, which ended Tuesday, were "serious and
constructive," State Department spokesman Philip Reeker told
reporters. "We made progress."
</P>
<P>
"They launched new negotiations on Agreed Framework
implementation," he added, referring to the 1994 deal, under which
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) agreed to freeze
its nuclear program in return for the West to help with fuel oil
and Western-designed light-water nuclear reactors. (US-DPRK-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Woldetensae said
here Tuesday his country is committed to working for peace to
settle the border dispute with neighboring Ethiopia in line with
the peace initiative of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
However, he accused Ethiopia of attempting to invade Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean minister, who leads his country's delegation to
the indirect talks with Ethiopia, was quoted by the Algerian News
Agency as saying the talks in Algiers are a good opportunity to
establish peace in the region. (Eritrea-Ethiopia-Conflict)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- The World Health Organization (WHO) has warned that
tobacco is dangerous and up to 11,000 people die everyday due to a
tobacco-related disease.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco advertisements talk to us from our streets, films,
radios, television sets and sports events. Everywhere our children
and we turn, there is something or someone telling you to smoke,"
said WHO Director-General Gro Harlem Brundtland in a statement to
be issued on World No Tobacco Day (WNTD) which falls on May 31.
</P>
<P>
"What makes all this unacceptable and treacherous is that this
dangerous and addictive product is sold to youth and adolescents
as an assertion of their freedom to choose," she said. (WHO-
Tobacco Day) 
</P>
