<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smog Kills 5,000 in Canada Annually: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 30 (Xinhua) -- Smog affects 20 million Canadians
and causes 5,000 premature deaths every year, a toll higher than
car accidents or breast cancer, Canadian Environment Commissioner
Richard Smith said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Commons, the environment commissioner said
smog kills more Canadians compared with breast cancer, which
causes 4,946 deaths annually, or prostate cancer, which claims 3,
622 each year.
</P>
<P>
It is also more deadly than either motor vehicle accidents or
malignant melanoma, which kill an annual 3,622 and 665
respectively, according to the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
He warned of an increasing number of vehicles eroding air
improvements achieved in the country over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, what we're seeing is an erosion of past gains and
people are seeing the problem is even more serious than we thought
10 years ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Environment Minister David Anderson also stated
Tuesday that he is negotiating with provinces on a national
strategy to control air pollutants.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, the minister said the government would do its
best to reduce toxic microscopic particles and would use
legislation, if necessary, to fight smog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
