<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barthez on Brink to Join Man United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 30 (Xinhua) -- French World Cup-winning goalkeeper
Fabien Barthez is expected to be confirmed as a Manchester United
player on Wednesday following his big-money transfer from Monaco.
</P>
<P>
Barthez completed his medical for United on Tuesday afternoon
before jetting back to join his country's Euro 2000 squad.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman was taken to the Alexandra private hospital in
Cheadle at lunchtime and returned to Old Trafford for further
tests before leaving the ground in a club car after three more
hours.
</P>
<P>
He later headed to the airport and is not now set to return to
Old Trafford until pre-season training starts in July - providing
there are no problems with the medicals.
</P>
<P>
The fee is estimated between 8 million and 10 million pounds
and could therefore be a world record for a goalkeeper, and the
Monaco ace has reportedly agreed a six-year contract worth 45,000
pounds-a-week.
</P>
<P>
United manager Sir Alex Ferguson said: "The first thing which
attracted me to Fabien is that he is an outstanding goalkeeper.
But after Peter Schmeichel we needed a little bit more than that."
</P>
<P>
"Peter had a great presence and a wonderful personality which
rubbed off on the rest of the team. Mark Bosnich and Raimond van
der Gouw are both terrific goalkeepers - but neither have quite
the personality which Schmeichel possessed," he said. "But Fabien
has.He is a real character. He's bouncy and bubbly, just like
Schmeichel was, and hopefully he is going to have a similar
influence on the rest of the team."
</P>
<P>
When Schmeichel quit United last summer Ferguson almost
captured the flamboyant Barthez then only for the deal to collapse.
</P>
<P>
He instead signed Bosnich, who has had a difficult season and
whose future must now be in grave doubt.
</P>
<P>
Also certainly on the way out is Italian Massimo Taibi, shipped
back home on loan with Reggina after a catalogue of embarrassing
mistakes following his 4.5 million pounds move from Venezia.
</P>
<P>
United finished the season with the dependable van der Gouw in
goal. But the Dutchman is approaching the end of his career, and
there was a clear need for a more reliable goalkeeper than Bosnich
or Taibi turned out to be.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson had hoped to keep details of Barthez's transfer under
wraps until the goalkeeper had completed his medical tests.
</P>
<P>
He was desperate to avoid a repeat of the embarrassment he
suffered when Ruud van Nistelrooy's 18 million pounds move from
PSV Eindhoven was called off after the striker failed his medical.
</P>
<P>
The United boss said: "Medicals these days are very thorough
because of the amount of money involved. But there are no worries
about Barthez's fitness, and I am confident we will be given the
go-ahead by the doctors to complete the transfer." 
</P>
</TEXT>
