<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends UNFICYP Mandate Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday recommended the extension of the mandate of the
United Nations Peacekeeping Force In Cyprus (UNFICYP) for a
further period of six months until December 15, 2000.
</P>
<P>
In his report, Annan said that during the past six months, the
situation along the cease-fire lines had remained stable and the
UNFICYP had continued to carry out its mandate tasks with the
cooperation of both sides.
</P>
<P>
"Two positive developments are worth noting. One is the
increase in contacts between Greek and Turkish Cypriots, which are
an important factor in improving the political climate on the
island," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"The other development is the welcome decision by the Turkish
Cypriot authorities to lift unnecessary onerous measures affecting
visits to the Greek Cypriot in the north," Annan noted.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, the presence of the UNFICYP on
the island remained indispensable for the maintenance of the cease-
fire between the two sides, Annan added.
</P>
<P>
The UNFICYP was set up in 1964. 
</P>
</TEXT>
