<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Renews U.N. Mission in W. Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday adopted a resolution to extend the mandate of the U.N.
Mission in Western Sahara (MINURSO) for two months, hoping that
relevant parties would agree on specific proposals to hold the
long-delayed referendum.
</P>
<P>
Namibia voted against the draft resolution while two other
member states, Mali and Jamaica, voted in abstentions.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted by the 15 Council members after
they met in a closed-door session on Tuesday to consider a report
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who, in his report to the
Security Council last Tuesday, called on Morocco and the Polisario
Front to come up with specific solutions to problems that have
delayed a referendum on the future of Western Sahara for more than
eight years.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council decides to extend the mandate of MINURSO
until July 31," the resolution said, "with the expectation that
the parties will offer the Secretary-General's Personal Envoy
specific and concrete proposals that can be agreed to in order to
resolve the multiple problems relating to the implementation of
the Settlement Plan."
</P>
<P>
Or, the parties will "be prepared to consider ways to achieve
an early, durable and agreed resolution to their dispute over
Western Sahara," the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The current mandate of MINURSO expires on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his report, said face-to-face talks held on May 14
in London under the auspices of his special envoy, former U.S.
Secretary of State James Baker, only reinforced the U.N.
assessment of "their widely divergent positions."
</P>
<P>
Also, "neither side offered any constructive suggestions on
the way forward" at their first direct talks conducted by Baker
since 1997, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has long been trying to organize a
referendum to decide whether Western Sahara should be incorporated
in Morocco, which controls most of the former Spanish colony, or
become independent, as sought by the Polisario Front.
</P>
<P>
But the referendum, first set for January 1992, has been
repeatedly postponed due to differences over who should be
eligible to vote.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
