<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank said Wednesday
that it has approved a credit of 150 million U.S. dollars for the
rural energy project in Vietnam that will provide energy to about
450,000 households in 32 provinces in the Southeast Asian country.
</P>
<P>
The bank's board of executive directors also discussed the
Vietnam Country Assistance Strategy Progress Report and commended
the report for its quality and frankness, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The rural energy project will provide reliable lighting sources
and improved health care and services through renewable energy. It
will also increase the productivity and incomes of rural residents
by creating alternative sources of energy for irrigation and other
productive activities.
</P>
<P>
The project will help the government realize its Country
Assistance Strategy objectives of equitable economic growth,
according to Anil Malhotra, the project's task manager.
</P>
<P>
"The project directly addresses equity and poverty in rural
areas by providing access and opportunity to over two million
rural people living on less than one dollar a day," Malhotra said.
