<HEADLINE> OAS Not To Impose Sanction on Peru: Congressman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian Congress Foreign Relations
Commission chairman Oswaldo Sandoval said Wednesday that it is
clear that after the Organization of American States (OAS)
Permanent Council meeting Peru will not be admonished for the
controversial elections of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
That council determined Wednesday to transfer the discussion of
the Peruvian electoral crisis to the Dialogue of Foreign Ministers
to be held before the upcoming OAS General Assembly, foreseen for
June 6 and 7 in Windsor, Canada.
</P>
<P>
This agreement was approved by consensus after the United
States withdrew, for lack of support, a proposal for the Peruvian
crisis to be discussed at the Windsor meeting and "within the
range of OAS Resolution 1080" which imposes sanctions on the
countries that violate constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
Sandoval said at a press conference that "the firm and clear
position" of the Latin American countries "forced the United
States to withdraw its proposal for the matter to be discussed at
the General Assembly."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position, seconded by Costa Rica, received the support
of 15 of the 34 ambassadors of the countries that form the
Permanent Council, while the majority of the Latin American
countries abstained from backing it up.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian elections were held Sunday without the
participation of opposition candidate Alejandro Toledo, and with
the absence of the international observers, who withdrew several
hours before the start of the process, for which the opposition
consider them illegitimate.
</P>
<P>
Toledo, the candidate of the Peru Posible coalition, refused to
take part in the voting because he considered that he was
dispossessed of the triumph in the first round held on April 9
through "fraud," and that there would be another in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
The election was held in the middle of uncertainty, and the
Electoral Processes National Office said that by the time that 99,
78 percent of the votes cast had been computed (11,779,504 votes),
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori had obtained 51.22 percent of
the suffrages.
</P>
<P>
Toledo had 17.68 percent, and the null or vitiated votes
represented 29.83 percent, and blank ballots 1.19 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
