<HEADLINE> COE Member States Urged to Implement European Court Rulings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Cyprus Wednesday called
on all Council of Europe (COE) member states to implement the
European Court of Human Rights rulings.
</P>
<P>
"All COE member states have a legal obligation to fully
implement the European Court of Human Rights decisions," the Greek
Foreign Ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that in the opposite case the convention on
human rights and relevant international law regulations were
violated and as a result a huge problem was created because the
principles, the institution and the credibility of the COE was
shattered.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Alternate Foreign Minister Elizabeth Papazoi and
Cyprus Attorney General Alecos Markides Wednesday chaired a
meeting in Athens to coordinate the two countries' efforts so that
the court decision in the case of Greek Cypriot Titina Loizidou
against Turkey is implemented.
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, The European Court ruled that Turkey is
guilty of violating Loizidou's human rights to enjoy peacefully
her property in the Turkish occupied part of Cyprus and be allowed
to access to it.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered Turkey to pay some 900,000 U.S. dollars
in compensation for Loizidou. 
</P>
