<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankruptcies Fall as Canada Sees Robust Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There were 6,715 cases of bankruptcy in April, a decline of 18.
1 percent from 8,201 recorded in March. The rate is also 8.9
percent lower than a year earlier, when the country registered a
total of 7,371 bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
The government bankruptcy report for April shows that consumer
bankruptcies dropped 9.3 percent to 5,929 from 6,535 for the same
month of last year. Business bankruptcies totaled 788, down 5.7
percent from 836 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The drop of bankruptcies was reported as the country yielded an
18-month GDP growth streak. Although the growth fell for the first
time in February, the economy was still rated 3.8 percent higher
than the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Nova Scotia, one of the major financial
institutions in Canada, has forecast a GDP increase of 4.4 percent
for Canada this year to outperform all other G-7 countries except
the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
