<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Mostly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 31 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell mostly
Wednesday despite the several encouraging economic reports that
show a slowdown in the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 4.80 at 10,522.33.
The blue chip index rose 227.89 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The technology heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 58.57 at 3,400.
91, trimming its biggest percentage gain in the previous session.
The composite rose 254.37 points or 7.94 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower mostly. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 1.85 at 1,420.60.
</P>
<P>
Stocks moved up and down and finally closed lower in a volatile
market as investors viewed signs of slower economic growth with
skepticism. The Conference Board said in a report that the Index
of Leading Economic Indicators, a key gauge of future economic
activities, dipped 0.1 percent in April after a 0.1 percent
increase in March.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Purchasing Management Association of Chicago
said in a separate report that the group's index of area business
activity fell to 53.9 in May from 56.5 in April. The Commerce
Department also reported that sales of new homes tumbled 5.8
percent in April, marking the largest decline since last September.
</P>
<P>
The three reports were encouraging. But investors did not
believe that the new data would encourage the Federal Reserve to
end the circle of interest rate increase.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised rates six times since last June
in an effort to cool off the economy and keep inflation under
control. The rate hikes have hit the stock market heavily.
</P>
<P>
Investors sold some of the tech stocks that rose Tuesday. Banks
and brokerages were mostly higher.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 2.22 at 643.60 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 7.12 at 904.97. But the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 0.55 at 476.18.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,715 up, 1,290 down and 439
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 950.32 million shares from 835.26
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
