<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Launches Expo 2000 World Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOVER, Germany, May 31 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest fair
was launched here Wednesday evening when German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder called for a "more open world" as the Expo 2000 would
present.
</P>
<P>
Giving a speech to some 3,000 guests celebrating the fair, the
German chancellor said the world must be more tolerant and open in
an era full of new scientific findings and technical breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
"A closed society must block the development of itself and the
whole world," he said, adding the Expo 2000 should show a "really
tolerant and world-open Germany."
</P>
<P>
"We all, and especially the Germans, must become
internationals," he said.
</P>
<P>
For 10 years, Germany has planned this "project of image"
since it reunited, according to Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
"Many have changed in this decade, not only with us, but also
in the total world, " he said. "The Expo 2000 is a great
exhibition to show these rapid changes with all of their sequences.
"
</P>
<P>
The Expo 2000 has no new topic, but it will show "the best of
cultures in more than 170 countries and regions, from the latest
findings in science to traditional arts," said the Deutsche Messe
AG which organized the fair.
</P>
<P>
"Humankind, nature, and technology" in the world are what the
Expo 2000 wants to present its 250,000 expected visitors Thursday
when it first opens the door to the public.
</P>
<P>
Besides striking and differently-styled national pavilions,
the fair also constructed a cultural-focused "Theme Park," where a
"Faust Hall" was left for the most famous German poem by Johan
Wolfgang von Goethe.
</P>
<P>
Expo chief Brigit Breuel hoped the Expo 2000 would be able to
compare with another world fair at the beginning of last century,
the World Fair in Paris in 1900.
</P>
<P>
Totally, the Mess AG projected over 40 million visitors from
all over the world in the coming 153 days, and a press official
told Xinhua more than 15,000 reporters had registered to cover the
fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
