<DOCNO> XIE20000531.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Assess Response to Crisis in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Spokesman Fred Eckhard said the team headed by Gen. Manfred
Eisele, formerly U.N. assistant secretary-general for peacekeeping
operations, was scheduled to leave New York Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.N. Mission in Sierra Leone, known as the
UNAMSIL, reported from Freetown that the military situation
throughout the west African country was relatively quiet with no
fighting between U.N. peacekeepers and rebel fighters belonging to
the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) for the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The RUF abducted more than 500 U.N. peacekeepers in early May.
Under the international pressure, it has released most of the U.N.
detainees, but is still surrounding more than 250 U.N. staff.
Negotiations are ongoing to restore U.N. personnel's freedom of
movement, according to Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
The UNAMSIL has increased its strength to 11,280 up to
Wednesday with more reinforcements to follow.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has called for a total of 16,
500 U.N. troops or more to ensure peace and the democratic process
in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
